# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alice-bache-gould
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Spending his early life in Switzerland, he received a PhD at the University of Erlangen and a medical degree at the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] After studying with Georges Cuvier and Alexander von Humboldt in Paris, Agassiz was appointed professor of natural history at the University of Neuchâtel.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He emigrated to the United States in 1847 after visiting Harvard University.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He went on to become professor of zoology and geology at Harvard, to head its Lawrence Scientific School, and to found its Museum of Comparative Zoology.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz is known for observational data gathering and analysis.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He made institutional and scientific contributions to zoology, geology, and related areas, including multivolume research books running to thousands of pages.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He is particularly known for his contributions to ichthyological classification, including of extinct species such as megalodon, and to the study of historical geology, including the founding of glaciology.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] His theories on human, animal and plant polygenism have been criticised as implicitly supporting scientific racism.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Louis Agassiz was born on May 28, 1807, in Môtier, a hamlet within the municipality of Haut-Vully (now part of Mont-Vully), in the Swiss canton of Fribourg.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He was the son of Louis Benjamin Rodolphe Agassiz and Rose Mayor.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] His father was a Protestant clergyman, as had been his progenitors for six generations, and his mother was the daughter of a physician and an intellectual in her own right, who had assisted her husband in the education of their children.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Louis Agassiz was educated at home until he spent four years at secondary school in Bienne, which he entered in 1818 and completed his elementary studies in Lausanne.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz studied at the University of Zurich, Heidelberg University, and the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] At the last one, he extended his knowledge of natural history, especially of botany.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1829, he received the degree of doctor of philosophy at the University of Erlangen and, in 1830, that of doctor of medicine at the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Moving to Paris, he came under the tutelage of Alexander von Humboldt and later received his financial benevolence.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Humboldt and Georges Cuvier launched him on his careers of respectively geology and zoology.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Ichthyology soon became a focus of Agassiz's life's work.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1819 to 1820, the German biologists Johann Baptist von Spix and Carl Friedrich Philipp von Martius undertook an expedition to Brazil.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] They returned home to Europe with many natural objects, including an important collection of the freshwater fish of Brazil, especially of the Amazon River.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Spix, who died in 1826, likely from a tropical disease, did not live long enough to work out the history of those fish, and Martius selected Agassiz for this project.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz threw himself into the work with an enthusiasm that would go on to characterize the rest of his life's work.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The task of describing the Brazilian fish was completed and published in 1829.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] It was followed by research into the history of fish found in Lake Neuchâtel.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Enlarging his plans, he in 1830 issued a prospectus of a *History of the Freshwater Fish of Central Europe*.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1839, however, the first part of the publication appeared, and it was completed in 1842.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In November 1832, Agassiz was appointed professor of natural history at the University of Neuchâtel, at a salary of about US$400 and declined brilliant offers in Paris because of the leisure for private study that that position afforded him.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The fossil fish in the rock of the surrounding region, the slates of Glarus and the limestones of Monte Bolca, soon attracted his attention.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] At the time, very little had been accomplished in their scientific study.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz as early as 1829, planned the publication of a work.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] More than any other, it would lay the foundation of his worldwide fame.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Five volumes of his *Recherches sur les poissons fossiles* (*Research on Fossil Fish*) were published from 1833 to 1843.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] They were magnificently illustrated, chiefly by Joseph Dinkel.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In gathering materials for that work, Agassiz visited the principal museums in Europe.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Meeting Cuvier in Paris, he received much encouragement and assistance from him.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1833, he married Cecile Braun, the sister of his friend Alexander Braun and established his household at Neuchâtel.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Trained to scientific drawing by her brothers, his wife was of the greatest assistance to Agassiz, with some of the most beautiful plates in *fossil* and *freshwater* fishes being drawn by her.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz found that his palaeontological analyses required a new ichthyological classification.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The fossils that he examined rarely showed any traces of the soft tissues of fish but instead, consisted chiefly of the teeth, scales, and fins, with the bones being perfectly preserved in comparatively few instances.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He therefore adopted a classification that divided fish into four groups (ganoids, placoids, cycloids, and ctenoids), based on the nature of the scales and other dermal appendages.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] That did much to improve fish taxonomy, but Agassiz's classification has since been superseded.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] With Louis de Coulon, both father and son, he founded the *Societé des Sciences Naturelles*, of which he was the first secretary and in conjunction with the Coulons also arranged a provisional museum of natural history in the orphan's home.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz needed financial support to continue his work.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The British Association and the Earl of Ellesmere, then Lord Francis Egerton, stepped in to help.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The 1290 original drawings made for the work were purchased by the Earl and presented by him to the Geological Society of London.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1836, the Wollaston Medal was awarded to Agassiz by the council of that society for his work on fossil ichthyology.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1838, he was elected a foreign member of the Royal Society.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Meanwhile, invertebrate animals engaged his attention.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Before Agassiz's first visit to England in 1834, Hugh Miller and other geologists had brought to light the remarkable fossil fish of the Old Red Sandstone of the northeast of Scotland.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The strange forms of *Pterichthys*, *Coccosteus*, and other genera were then made known to geologists for the first time.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1838, Frederick William III of Prussia founded the Neuchâtel Academy which owes its birth to the impetus of Louis Agassiz.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The young scholar endowed with exceptional charisma was recruited by the authorities of the Principality of Neuchâtel as early as 1832.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In the early stages of his career in Neuchatel, Agassiz also made a name for himself as a man who could run a scientific department well.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Under his care, the University of Neuchâtel soon became a leading institution for scientific inquiry.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] From 1836 onwards, Agassiz became increasingly interested in glaciers.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] At a time when Swiss glaciers were still advancing, the hypothesis of an extensive past glaciation emerged in scientific circles.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] On 24 July 1837, in his speech at the annual meeting of the Swiss Academy of Natural Sciences in Neuchâtel, which he chaired, he presented this new theory, although a lecture on fossil fish was expected.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] To support the Ice Age theory, he traveled the Alps in search of traces of previous glacial movements.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The research conducted on the Unteraargletscher between 1840 and 1845 was groundbreaking.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] At that time, his companions added the Agassizhorn to the list of mountains of Switzerland named after people.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1842 to 1846, Agassiz issued his *Nomenclator Zoologicus*, a classification list with references of all names used in zoological genera and groups.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1843.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] After his departure for the United States, his strong commitment to the public dissemination of knowledge and to the defense of women's education would play a decisive role in the affirmation of science in America.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The vacation of 1836 was spent by Agassiz and his wife in the little village of Bex, where he met Jean de Charpentier and Ignaz Venetz.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Their recently announced glacial theories had startled the scientific world, and Agassiz returned to Neuchâtel as an enthusiastic convert.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1837, Agassiz proposed that the Earth had been subjected to a past ice age.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He presented the theory to the Helvetic Society that ancient glaciers flowed outward from the Alps, and even larger glaciers had covered the plains and mountains of Europe, Asia, and North America and smothered the entire Northern Hemisphere in a prolonged ice age.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In the same year, he was elected a foreign member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Those ideas attracted the attention of Agassiz, and he discussed them with Charpentier and Schimper, whom he accompanied on successive trips to the Alps.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz even had a hut constructed upon one of the Aar Glaciers and for a time made it his home to investigate the structure and movements of the ice.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz visited England, and with William Buckland, the only English naturalist who shared his ideas, made a tour of the British Isles in search of glacial phenomena, and became satisfied that his theory of an ice age was correct.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1840, Agassiz published a two-volume work, *Études sur les glaciers* ("Studies on Glaciers").
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In it, he discussed the movements of the glaciers, their moraines, and their influence in grooving and rounding the rocks and in producing the striations and *roches moutonnées* seen in Alpine-style landscapes.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The publication of the work gave fresh impetus to the study of glacial phenomena in all parts of the world.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Familiar then with recent glaciation, Agassiz and the English geologist William Buckland visited the mountains of Scotland in 1840.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] There, they found clear evidence in different locations of glacial action.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The discovery was announced to the Geological Society of London in successive communications.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The mountainous districts of England, Wales, and Ireland were understood to have been centres for the dispersion of glacial debris.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In his later years, Agassiz applied his glacial theories to the geology of the Brazilian tropics, including the Amazon.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz began with a working hypothesis which could be tested by the results of fieldwork to find either inconclusive, or conclusively supporting or refuting evidence.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] A hypothesis that can be conclusively refuted is better than a hypothesis that is difficult to test.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz had a close association with his student and field assistant, the geologist Charles Hartt who eventually refuted Agassiz's theories about the Amazon based on his fieldwork there.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Instead of evidence for any glacial processes, he found chemically weathered sediments from marine and tropical fluvial, not glacial, processes, a finding that later geologists confirmed.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz hypothesis that the Amazon was affected by the Last Glacial Maximum (LGM) was correct, although the mechanism causing the effect was non-glacial.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The Amazon rainforest was split into two large blocks by extensive savanna during the LGM.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The financial offers that were presented to him in the United States induced him to settle there, where he remained to the end of his life.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He was elected a foreign honorary member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1846.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1846, still married to Cecilie, who remained with their three children in Switzerland, Agassiz met Elizabeth Cabot Cary at a dinner.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The two developed a romantic attachment, and when his wife died in 1848, they made plans to marry.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The ceremony took place on April 25, 1850, in Boston, Massachusetts at King's Chapel.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz brought his children to live with them, and Elizabeth raised and developed close relationships with her step-children.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz had a mostly cordial relationship with the Harvard botanist Asa Gray despite their disagreements.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz believed each human race had been separately created, but Gray, a supporter of Charles Darwin, believed in the shared evolutionary ancestry of all humans.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In addition, Agassiz was a member of the Scientific Lazzaroni, a group of mostly physical scientists who wanted American academia to mimic the more autocratic academic structures of European universities, but Gray was a staunch opponent of that group.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz's engagement for the Lowell Institute lectures precipitated the establishment in 1847 of the Lawrence Scientific School at Harvard University, with Agassiz as its head.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Harvard appointed him professor of zoology and geology, and he founded the Museum of Comparative Zoology there in 1859 and served as its first director until his death in 1873.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] During his tenure at Harvard, Agassiz studied the effect of the last ice age in North America.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In his "Contributions to the Natural History of the United States," he critically examined Darwin's theory of evolution.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He believed that God created new life after each ice age and that it was the responsibility of naturalists to understand this plan of creation.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] By defending this view, he gained the favor of the American readership.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In August 1857, Agassiz was offered the chair of palaeontology in the Museum of Natural History, Paris, which he refused.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He was later decorated with the Cross of the Legion of Honor.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz continued his lectures for the Lowell Institute.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1850, he had married Elizabeth Cabot Cary, who later wrote introductory books about natural history and a lengthy biography of her husband after he had died.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz served as a nonresident lecturer at Cornell University while he was also on faculty at Harvard.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1852, he accepted a medical professorship of comparative anatomy at Charlestown, Massachusetts, but he resigned in two years.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] From then on, Agassiz's scientific studies dropped off, but he became one of the best-known scientists in the world.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] By 1857, Agassiz was so well-loved that his friend Henry Wadsworth Longfellow wrote "The Fiftieth Birthday of Agassiz" in his honor and read it at a dinner given for Agassiz by the Saturday Club in Cambridge.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz's own writing continued with four (of a planned 10) volumes of *Natural History of the United States*, published from 1857 to 1862.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He also published a catalog of papers in his field, *Bibliographia Zoologiae et Geologiae*, in four volumes between 1848 and 1854.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1863, Agassiz was among the founding members of the National Academy of Sciences, established by an act of the United States Congress to provide scientific advice to the federal government.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Stricken by ill health in the 1860s, Agassiz resolved to return to the field for relaxation and to resume his studies of Brazilian fish.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In April 1865, he led the Thayer Expedition to Brazil.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] While there, he commissioned two photographers, Augusto Stahl and George Leuzinger, to accompany the expedition and produce somatological images of Indigenous people and enslaved Africans and Black people.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] After his return in August 1866, an account of the expedition, *A Journey in Brazil*, was published in 1868.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In December 1871, he made a second eight-month excursion, known as the *Hassler* expedition under the command of Commander Philip Carrigan Johnson (the brother of Eastman Johnson) and visited South America on its southern Atlantic and Pacific Seaboards.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The ship explored the Magellan Strait, which drew the praise of Charles Darwin.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Following the establishment of the first U.S.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in New York City in 1866, Agassiz was called on to help settle disputes about animal behavior.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He deemed the way turtles were shipped caused them suffering, while P.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Barnum argued with Agassiz' support that his snakes would eat only live animals.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] His second wife, Elizabeth Cary Agassiz, assisted him in preparing his *A Journey in Brazil*.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Along with her stepson, Alexander Agassiz, she wrote *Seaside Studies in Natural History* and *Marine Animals of Massachusetts*.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] These were weeks of exquisite delight to Agassiz.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] From his first marriage to Cecilie Braun, Agassiz had two daughters, Ida and Pauline, and a son, Alexander.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1863, Agassiz's daughter Ida married Henry Lee Higginson, who later founded the Boston Symphony Orchestra and was a benefactor to Harvard and other schools.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] On November 30, 1860, Agassiz's daughter Pauline was married to Quincy Adams Shaw (1825–1908), a wealthy Boston merchant and later a benefactor to the Boston Museum of Fine Arts.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Pauline Agassiz Shaw later became a prominent educator, suffragist, and philanthropist.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In the last years of his life, Agassiz worked to establish a permanent school in which zoological science could be pursued amid the living subjects of its study.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The school collapsed soon after Agassiz's death but is considered to be a precursor of the nearby Woods Hole Marine Biological Laboratory.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz had a profound influence on the American branches of his two fields and taught many future scientists who would go on to prominence, including Alpheus Hyatt, David Starr Jordan, Joel Asaph Allen, Joseph Le Conte, Ernest Ingersoll, William James, Charles Sanders Peirce, Orestes St.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] John, Nathaniel Shaler, Samuel Hubbard Scudder, Alpheus Packard, and his son Alexander Emanuel Agassiz.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He had a profound impact on the paleontologist Charles Doolittle Walcott and the natural scientist Edward S.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz had a reputation for being a demanding teacher.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Those and other recollections were collected and published by Lane Cooper in 1917, which Ezra Pound would draw on for his anecdote of Agassiz and the sunfish.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In the early 1840s, Agassiz named two fossil fish species after Mary Anning (*Acrodus anningiae* and *Belenostomus anningiae*) and another after her friend, Elizabeth Philpot.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Anning was a paleontologist known around the world for important finds, but because of her gender, she was often not formally recognized for her work.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz was grateful for the help that the women gave him in examining fossil fish specimens during his visit to Lyme Regis in 1834.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz died in Cambridge, Massachusetts, in 1873 and was buried on the Bellwort Path at Mount Auburn Cemetery, joined later by his wife.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] His monument is a boulder from a glacial moraine of the Aar near the site of the old Hôtel des Neuchâtelois, not far from the spot where his hut once stood.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] His grave is sheltered by pine trees from his old home in Switzerland.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The Cambridge elementary school north of Harvard University was named in his honor, and the surrounding neighborhood became known as "Agassiz" as a result.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The school's name was changed to the Maria L.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Baldwin School on May 21, 2002, because of concerns about Agassiz's involvement in scientific racism and to honor Maria Louise Baldwin, the African-American principal of the school, who served from 1889 to 1922.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The neighborhood, however, continued to be known as Agassiz. c.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] 2009, neighborhood residents decided to rename the neighborhood's community council as the "Agassiz-Baldwin Community".
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Then, in July 2021, culminating a two-year effort on the part of neighborhood residents, the Cambridge City Council voted unanimously to change the name to the Baldwin Neighborhood.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] An elementary school, the Agassiz Elementary School in Minneapolis, Minnesota, existed from 1922 to 1981.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz Glacier in Montana, Agassiz Creek in Glacier National Park, Agassiz Glacier in the Saint Elias Mountains of Alaska, and Mount Agassiz in the White Mountains of New Hampshire also bear his name.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] A crater on Mars, *Crater Agassiz*, and a promontorium on the moon are also named in his honor.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Cape Agassiz, a headland situated in Palmer Land, Antarctica, is named in his honor.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] A main-belt asteroid, 2267 Agassiz, is also named in association with him.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 2005, the European Geosciences Union Division on Cryospheric Sciences established the Louis Agassiz Medal, awarded to individuals in recognition of their outstanding scientific contribution to the study of the cryosphere on Earth or elsewhere in the Solar System.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz took part in a monthly gathering called the Saturday Club at the Parker House, a meeting of Boston writers and intellectuals.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 1850, Agassiz commissioned daguerreotypes, which were described as "haunting and voyeuristic" of the enslaved Renty Taylor and Taylor's daughter, Delia, to further his arguments about black inferiority.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] They are the earliest known photographs of enslaved persons.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz left the images to Harvard, and they remained in the Peabody Museum's attic until 1976, when they were rediscovered by Ellie Reichlin, a former staff member.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The 15 daguerrotypes were in a case with the embossing "J.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Zealy, Photographer, Columbia," with several handwritten labels, which helped in later identification.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Reichlin spent months doing research to try to identify the people in the photos, but Harvard University did not make efforts to contact the families and licensed the photos for use.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 2011, Tamara Lanier wrote a letter to the president of Harvard that identified herself as a direct descendant of the Taylors and asked the university to turn over the photos to her.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 2019, Taylor's descendants sued Harvard for the return of the images and unspecified damages.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] The lawsuit was supported by 43 living descendants of Agassiz, who wrote in a letter of support, "For Harvard to give the daguerreotypes to Ms.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Lanier and her family would begin to make amends for its use of the photos as exhibits for the white supremacist theory Agassiz espoused." Everyone must evaluate fully "his role in promoting a pseudoscientific justification for white supremacy." Settlement of the lawsuit was announced in May 2025.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] All of the Agassiz-Zealy daguerrotypes are expected to be transferred to a museum of African-American history in South Carolina (none go to Ms.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Lanier personally), and Harvard is to pay an undisclosed monetary sum to Ms.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz was a well-known natural scientist of his generation in America.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In addition to being a natural scientist, Agassiz wrote prolifically in the field of scientific polygenism after he came to the United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Upon arriving in Boston in 1846, Agassiz spent a few months acquainting himself with the northeast region of the United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He spent much of his time with Samuel George Morton, a famous American anthropologist at the time who became well known by analyzing fossils brought back by Lewis and Clark.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] One of Morton’s personal projects involved studying cranial capacity of human skulls from around the world.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Morton aimed to use craniometry to prove that white people were biologically superior to other races.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] His work "*Crania Aegyptiaca"* claimed to support the polygenism belief that the races were created separately and each had their own unique attributes.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Morton relied on other scientists to send him skulls along with information about where they were acquired.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Factors that can affect cranial capacity, such as body size and gender, were not taken into consideration by Morton.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He made questionable judgment calls such as dismissing Hindu skull calculations from his Caucasian cranial measurements because they brought the overall average down.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Oppositely, he included Peruvian skull measurements alongside Native American calculations even though the Peruvian numbers lowered the average score.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Despite Morton's unsound methods, his published work on cranial capacities across races was deemed authoritative in the United States and Europe.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Morton is a primary influence on Agassiz's belief in polygenism.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] John Amory Lowell invited Agassiz to present twelve lectures in December 1846 on three subjects titled "*The Plan of Creation as shown in the Animal Kingdom*, *Ichthyology,* and *Comparative Embryology"* as a part of the Lowell Lecture series.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] These lectures were widely attended with up to 5,000 people in attendance on some nights.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] It was during these lectures that Agassiz announced for the first time that black and white people had different origins but were part of the same species.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz repeated this lecture 10 months later to the Charleston Literary Club but changed his original stance, claiming that black people were physiologically and anatomically a distinct species.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz believed that humans did not descend from one single common ancestor.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He believed that like plants and animals, various regions have differentiated species of humans**.** He considered this hypothesis testable, and matched to the available evidence.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He also indicated that there were obvious geographical barriers that were the likely cause of speciation.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Stephen Jay Gould asserted that Agassiz's observations sprang from racist bias, in particular from his revulsion on first encountering African-Americans in the United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Agassiz never supported slavery and claimed his views on polygenism had nothing to do with politics.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] However, his views on polygenism have emboldened proponents of segregationism.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Unlike Abraham Lincoln, who envisioned repatriating Black Americans to Africa, Agassiz believed their presence in America was irreversible.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] According to him, the liberation of slaves should be accompanied by strict legal provisions guaranteeing racial segregation to avoid "crossbreedings" which he saw as potentially giving birth to less fertile individuals.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Like other proponents of so-called scientific racism, Agassiz played a pioneering role in the development of systematic racial segregation.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He notably influenced Ezra Pound, Eugen Fischer, John Kasper and Stephen C.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] However, racist and sexist prejudices were also put forward by abolitionists as early as 1844-1845 during the trial brought by Sally Miller against her owners to obtain her emancipation.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Accusations of racism and segregationism against Agassiz have prompted the renaming of landmarks, schoolhouses, and other institutions (which abound in Massachusetts) that bear his name.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Opinions about those moves are often mixed, given his extensive scientific legacy in other areas, his racism has long been overshadowed in favor of his brilliant research in the natural sciences.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] After the Sonderbund War, the country pacified by Dufour had adopted a new Swiss Federal Constitution, inspired by the Constitution of the United States, founding the federal state in 1848.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 2017, the Swiss Alpine Club declined to revoke Agassiz's status as a member of honor, which he received in 1865 for his scientific work, because the club considered that removing Louis Agassiz from the list of former honorary members would be to falsify history.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Racism was first analyzed in Switzerland by the African-American writer James Baldwin during his 1953 visit to Leukerbad.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] He described it as a "naive" belief in the superiority of white culture and "race," which—unlike in the United States—did not reveal its violent side due to a lack of direct contact with enslaved or colonized people.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] Since the 1960s, intellectuals and researchers have taken a closer look at antisemitism and xenophobia in Switzerland.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In June 2019, Neuchâtel changed the name of Espace Louis-Agassiz, near the Faculty of Letters of the University of Neuchâtel area, to Espace Tilo-Frey.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] She was the first person of African descent elected to the National Council, in 1971, the year that Swiss voters approved giving women the right to vote and to stand for office in a referendum.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 2020, the Stanford Department of Psychology asked for a statue of Louis Agassiz to be removed from the front façade of its building.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] When another statue, that of Baron David de Pury, became a source of debate in Switzerland, the authorities in Neuchâtel opted to install a plaque and launched an artistic contest to create a work that interacted with the statue and its past.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] An international jury presided by Pap Ndiaye selected Genevan artist Mathias Pfund's sculpture *Great in the Concrete*, inspired by the 1906 fall of Agassiz's statue with head buried in concrete.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 2021, Chicago Public Schools announced they would remove Agassiz's name from an elementary school and rename it for the abolitionist and political activist, Harriet Tubman.
[src:alice-bache-gould/agassiz] In 2022, The Trustees of Reservations renamed Agassiz Rock as The Monoliths.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Sent home for her education, Bache Gould trained as a mathematician and undertook graduate studies in mathematics, teaching for a time at Carleton College, Minnesota.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Enrolled at MIT, she failed to complete her thesis and obtain the PhD, due to poor health.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Finding work as a mathematician subsequently proved difficult.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Being fluent in Spanish, she began subsequently to follow her true interest in Spanish-American studies, working for several years in the educational system of Puerto Rico.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] She abandoned mathematics for history and began to do research on the colonization of the Americas by Spain.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] World War I found her doing research in Madrid, where she promptly volunteered for war work at the American Embassy there, and, sent home, in the United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Subsequently, she found her way back to Spain, where she remained, doing research and publishing articles and a book on Agassiz.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] When the Spanish Civil War started, she retired to the United States, returning when it was over for the peak of her career.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] As a historian, her studies of Christopher Columbus and Queen Isabella I of Castile resulted in the most complete biographical account of Columbus' crew.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] In 1942, Gould became the only female corresponding member of Real Academia de la Historia and was awarded the Order of Isabella the Catholic (in 1952).
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Previously she had received other honors.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Gould never married or had any children.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] She had close relationships with a few female friends, carried on mainly by correspondence.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] There is no evidence of any sexual involvement with either sex.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] One friend joked about the low-cut dresses she wore to Puerto Rico.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] As a researcher in Spain she was a highly respected aging unmarried lady with greying hair.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Alice Bache Gould was born on January 5, 1868, in Cambridge, Massachusetts, to Benjamin Apthorp Gould (1824-1896) and Mary Apthorp Quincy Gould (1834-1883).
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Her mother was part of the Quincy political family and a descendant of Rev.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] George Phillips who settled Watertown, Massachusetts in 1630.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Her father, an astronomer, headed the Argentine National Observatory.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Alice lived briefly with her family in Cordoba, Argentina before being sent back to Cambridge in 1871, to live with relatives.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Alice lived mainly in the United States but frequently traveled to Argentina.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Tragically, while on a birthday trip to the River Rio Primero on February 8, 1874, her older sisters Susan Morton Quincy Gould and Lucretia Goddard Gould and their nurse Alvina Fontaine were swept away and drowned.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Alice and her younger siblings Mary and Benjamin were unable to help.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] In 1883, Alice Bache Gould suffered a further loss when her mother died.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Her father finally returned from Argentina in 1885.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Gould studied briefly at the Society for the Collegiate Instruction of Women in Cambridge (later Radcliffe College) in 1885, before attending Bryn Mawr College from 1886 to 1889.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] One of her close friends was Emily Greene Balch.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] She graduated from Bryn Mawr as a member of the school's second graduating class in 1889 with her A.B. in mathematics and physics.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] She went on to study at Massachusetts Institute of Technology and at Newnham College, Cambridge in England from 1890 to 1893.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Although Newnham allowed women to attend classes, it did not yet grant them degrees.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] After teaching briefly at Carleton College in Northfield, Minnesota, she became a graduate student in mathematics at the University of Chicago in 1894, studying with E.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] However, her father's death in 1896, the end of her fellowship, and poor health, prevented her from completing her thesis on Brocardian geometry, a type of geometry developed by Henri Brocard.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] She returned to Cambridge to recover her health.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] On November 17, 1897, Alice fulfilled one of her father's ambitions by donating $20,000 to the National Academy of Sciences for the Benjamin Apthorp Gould Fund to support researchers and "advance the science of astronomy".
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] *The New York Times* identified it at the time as "one of the largest funds in the country".
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] In 1901, Gould published a historical monograph on Louis Agassiz in Mark Antony De Wolfe Howe's series of *Beacon Biographies of Eminent Americans*.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] She was commended for her descriptions of Agassiz's personality and the Brazilian landscapes.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] In 1903 Gould traveled to Puerto Rico, where she spent much of the next seven years.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Gould started a "Porto Rico Teachers' Fund" to raise money for a nursing school around 1905.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] She was also a contributor to the Kissinger Relief Fund for the study of yellow fever in 1907, and was approached by Bailey K.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Ashford about supporting a Puerto Rican school of tropical medicine.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Later in life, between 1941 and 1947, Gould donated approximately 1,500 items on Puerto Rico to the United States Library of Congress.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] During her stay in South America, Gould became interested in the colonization of the Americas, and began to write an article on the early colonization of Barbados.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] In 1911, she went to Spain, stopping to do research on Christopher Columbus and Queen Isabella I of Castile at the Archivo de Simancas and other Spanish archives.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] She spent much of the rest of her life there.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] During World War I Gould went to the United States Embassy in Madrid where she volunteered in the espionage office.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] She led an effort to send female clerical workers to the embassy to assist staff there.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] In March 1918, she returned to Boston, expecting to remain there for only a few months.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] When she realized that she would not be able to return to Spain for some time, she tried to obtain war work in the United States that would allow her to use her mathematical training.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Few options were available, but she eventually had the choice of assisting Forest Ray Moulton at the Ordnance Department in Washington, D.C., doing "routine and monotonous" work as a "computer", or helping her former advisor, E.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Moore, to teach classes in navigation to Naval ROTC students at the University of Chicago.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] She chose to work with Moore, and enjoyed being useful to the war effort.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] She became particularly interested in the mathematical techniques of great-circle navigation, and began to write her own text on the subject.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] By 1919, she was no longer needed at the University of Chicago.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Gould's first published paper on Spanish colonization of the Americas appeared in the *Boletín de la Real Academia de la Historia* (the Bulletin of the Spanish Royal Academy of History) in 1924.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] In 1925, she returned to Spain to continue her Columbian researches.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Over the next 42 years, the results of her research were predominantly published there.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] During the Spanish Civil War in 1936 Gould returned briefly to Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] During this stay in Boston she supported another philanthropic cause.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] In 1937, she was a major contributor when the historical Josiah Quincy House became the property of the Society for the Preservation of New England Antiquities.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] After the Spanish civil war, Gould again returned to Spain.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] As a result of her researches, Gould was able to specifically identify the crew members who accompanied Columbus on his transatlantic voyage in 1492, to describe them and their historical situation in detail, and to correct a number of historical errors.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Gould's articles identified 87 of the 90 crewmen.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Her studies showed that only four of the Columbus crew had problems with the law, destroying the version that most of them were criminals and jailbirds.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] She also demonstrated that no Englishman, Irishman or other North European was aboard the Columbus ships. and proved that Pedro de Lepe, whose existence had long been disputed, had sailed with Columbus on the *Santa María*.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Gould found a certified copy of the document that recognized Columbus's descendants rights to his privileges, and was praised particularly for ability to read the penmanship of the court scribes.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] She is credited with saving documents that would otherwise have been discarded and destroyed.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] In 1942, Gould became the only female corresponding member of Real Academia de la Historia.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] In 1947, she became an honorary member of the Colonial Society of Massachusetts, the first woman to be accepted into membership.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] In 1952, she was awarded the Order of Isabella the Catholic, presented in Seville by Joaquin Ruiz Jimenez, the Spanish Minister of Education.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Six years before her death, Gould collapsed of sunstroke in the street, and was told to spend less time working.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Gould died of a cerebral hemorrhage on July 25, 1953, in the garden at Simancas Castle, near the archives.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Being of Congregationalist Protestant extraction, she is interred in the English Cemetery of Madrid, which is reserved for non-Catholics.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] A stone book on her grave is inscribed with her name.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] After her death, a plaque was placed at the entryway to honor "Miss Alice B.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Gould illustrious North American researcher and a great friend of Spain.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] She worked in this archive for forty years and died at its entrance on the 25 of July 1953”.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] The original Spanish reads: "A miss Alice B.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Gould, ilustre investigadora norteamericana y gran amiga de España. trabajó en este archivo durante cuarenta años y murió a su entrada el día 25 de julio de 1953".
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] A square in Simancas, Spain was named after her.
[src:alice-bache-gould/alice-bache-gould] Gould's papers and collected materials are contained in a number of archives, including the Massachusetts Historical Society, the United States Library of Congress, the Elmer Holmes Bobst Library in New York City, and the Spanish Royal Academy of History.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] The **General Archive of Simancas** (Spanish: *Archivo General de Simancas*, also known by its acronym, *AGS*) is an official archive located in the Castle of Simancas, in the town of Simancas, province of Valladolid, Castile and León, Spain.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] It was founded in 1540, making this the first official archive of the Crown of Castile.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] The chronological evolution of the institution has been influenced by the history of the Crown of Castile.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] The moments of strength or weakness of the Spanish monarchy have been reflected in the regularity of documents' arrivals or conversely in the shortages of resources.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] A major milestone occurred in 1588, when Philip II of Spain issued the charter of the Archives of Simancas, a key document for understanding the management of both this archive and others in the peninsula.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] Also, the damage suffered during the Spanish War of Independence (the Peninsular War) had a major impact on the institution.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] Currently, the AGS is a cultural institution funded by the Ministry of Culture of Spain dedicated to conservation, cataloging and research.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] These activities have brought about the reputation of the archive as one of the cornerstones of the Iberian Peninsula in its preservation and custody of documents.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] UNESCO awarded the General Archive of Simancas in 2017 by inscribing it on the Memory of the World International Register.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] The archive was placed in Simancas, a town some 10 km away from Valladolid.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] The place was chosen because it was well-fortified and easily defended.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] During the period of the Reconquista, the village of Simancas was relevant as a frontier zone.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] Subsequently, its strategic location between the kingdoms of León and Castile gave it a political role in that period.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] After the conquest of Toledo and its territory in 1085 the town lost its importance, and in the 13th century was just one of many towns on the outskirts of Valladolid.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] However, it soon ceased to be part of the jurisdiction of Valladolid, because in 1465 King Henry IV of Castile ceded some powers to the city of Simancas to encourage it to remain faithful to him.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] Until 1917, modern and contemporary historians dated Simancas castle to the time of the Reconquest.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] However, in that year Francisco Rodríguez Marín published a paper in which he stated that Simancas castle had been taken by Admiral Fadrique under Henry IV, and later was demolished and rebuilt by his son, Admiral Alonso Enriquez.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] Thus, the construction date of the current castle can be assigned between 1467 and 1480.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] The castle has been extensively renovated over the centuries, and few traces of its original structure remain.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] Factors that led to the decision to choose the castle of Simancas as an archive include the fact that, after advancing the frontiers of Christian territory to southern territories, the castle no longer had a specific function in peacetime.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] That meant that it had other uses, from being a weapons cache to acting as a state prison, functions that were served at the same time as being an archive.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] There was also the influence of Francisco de los Cobos, *Comendador Mayor de León*, a member of the Carlos I's Court who exerted all his influence in order to place the archive in Simancas.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] The castle was not a place designed to house an archive, which means that there are some problems that have concerned archivists throughout history.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] The most important of these is the risk of fire.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] In the past, sharing archive space with a jail increased the risk that the records might be reduced to ashes.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] Moreover, being a fortress, the building was a prime target in armed conflicts, such as the Spanish War of Independence of 1808–1814.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] The building was not designed to keep documents nor for research, so the ornamentation was not intended to extol scholarship but rather royal power.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] For example, one of the doors of the AGS was decorated with the coat of arms of king Philip II.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] Furthermore, it has long been difficult to accommodate the researchers.
[src:alice-bache-gould/archivo-de-simancas] Some improvements have been made over the years to address this trouble.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] The **Argentine National Observatory**, today the **Astronomical Observatory of Córdoba**, was founded on 24 October 1871, by Argentine president Domingo F.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Sarmiento and the North American astronomer Benjamin Apthorp Gould.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Its creation was the beginning of astronomical studies in Argentina.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Sarmiento was representing his country in the United States, he had the opportunity to meet pioneering astronomer Benjamin Apthorp Gould, who was very interested in traveling to Argentina in order to study the stellar south hemisphere.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Once Sarmiento was installed as President of Argentina, he invited Gould to travel to Argentina, in 1869, to provide his full support to organize an observatory.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] The same night of the inauguration of the Astronomical Observatory of Córdoba, Gould began with the naked eye, and later with the aid of small binoculars, a map of the southern sky, recording more than 7000 stars, which was published under the name of *Uranometría Argentina*.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] This work by Gould, Miles Rock and others formalized the southern constellations which were not as well documented as the northern ones.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] He remained as director of the observatory until 1885, when he returned to the United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] The first stellar photographs in the world – hundreds of sheets of open star clusters – were taken at this observatory.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] This helped to determine the exact position of each star.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Gould published the results in the *Catálogo de zonas estelares* (1884), the first systematic and large-scale astronomy book, including more than 70,000 stars of the southern hemisphere, and the Argentinian General Catalog, which contains about 35,000 stars.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] As part of the Córdoba Astronomical Observatory, the Meteorological Office was created by Sarmiento at Gould's suggestion in 1872, and is now known as the National Meteorological Service.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] The national network of meteorological stations and geomagnetic observatories was established in 1873.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] The Bosque Alegre Astrophysics Station is located about 30 miles southwest of Cordoba at an altitude of 1200 meters (3,937-ft) in the Sierras Chicas.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] The observatory was integral to the development of Argentine and Latin American Astrophysics.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] For example, the Atlas of Austral Galaxies by J.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] The 61-inch (1.54-meter) Great Reflector was the concept of the director of the Argentine National Observatory, Charles Dillon Perrine, who assumed the directorship in 1909.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] He had experience with the 36-in Crossley Reflector at Lick Observatory from 1900 to 1909.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] In 1912 the National Government approved Perrine's proposal to construct this telescope, equal to the largest in the world at that time.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] It would remain the largest in South America until 1981 when a larger one was built in Brazil.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] The mount and dome were contracted to Warner and Swasey of Cleveland, Ohio, USA.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] The glass block for the mirror was ordered from Saint-Gobain of France, completed in Dec.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] 1912, and delivered to Argentina in early 1913.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Due to the high price asked by George W.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Ritchey (USA) to figure (shape and polish) the glass into a mirror, Perrine decided to have the highly skilled staff technician, James Mulvey, do the work at the observatory itself in a purpose-built optics laboratory.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] This experience put Argentina at the forefront in this field.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Mulvey, the First World War, the rebuilding of the Observatory in the city of Córdoba, political challenges, and national economic limitations significantly delayed the project.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] In 1936, Perrine retired, having selected the site, constructed the station buildings, and assembled the telescope mount, but the mirror was not yet complete.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Aguilar and JJ Nissen, director of the National Observatory, assumed responsibility and the mirror was sent for completion to the Fecker optician in the US.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] At that time, the telescope was the third largest in the world.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] The first Argentine astrophysicist Enrique Gaviola went to the US in 1939 to receive the mirror.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Sadly, Fecker, even with its well-known expertise, could not complete the mirror.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Gaviola took control of the configuration (shaping and polishing) and completed it.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Finally, on July 5, 1942, after 33 years of work, the Astrophysical Station was inaugurated. “This Astrophysical Station was born in the optimistic and courageous mind of Charles Dillon Perrine, director of the Cordoba Observatory from 1909 to 1936.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Perrine dedicated the best energies of many years of his life to the realization in the matter of his daring dream.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] He had triumphs and defeats, successes and failures.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] " Words by Enrique Gaviola, inauguration speech of the Bosque Alegre Astrophysical Station, July 5, 1942.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] A 20-in (76-cm) telescope was obtained by Director Perrine and figured by Mulvey as practice before figuring the larger 61-inch (1.54-meter) mirror.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] It was the “first large reflecting telescope, designed, built entirely in Argentina (1913-18), and used with success”.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Later it was named the "Perrine" after C.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] Perrine, the Director from 1909 to 1936.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] It was first used at the Cordoba Observatory, then because of urban light pollution in the mid-1970's, it was moved to the High Altitude Station of the Félix Aguilar Astronomical Observatory in the province of San Juan.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] On November 18, 2011, the "Perrine" was re-located and installed in its own dome at Bosque Alegre.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] At this time the "Perrine" is the second largest telescope at Bosque Alegre and the fourth largest in Argentina.
[src:alice-bache-gould/argentine-national-observatory] It was put to work immediately and continues to be used to do the necessary validation of discoveries of celestial bodies located in different parts of the sky.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He was born in Boston, Massachusetts, the son of Lucretia Dana (Goddard) and Benjamin Apthorp Gould, the principal of Boston Latin School, which the younger Gould attended.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The poet Hannah Flagg Gould was his aunt.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He studied at Harvard College under Benjamin Peirce, graduating in 1844.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He studied mathematics and astronomy under C.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gauss at Göttingen, Germany, during which time he published approximately 20 papers on the observation and motion of comets and asteroids.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] (he was the first American to receive this degree in astronomy) he toured European observatories asking for advice on what could be done to further astronomy as a professional science in the U.S.A.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The main advice he received was to start a professional journal modeled after what was then the world's leading astronomical publication, the *Astronomische Nachrichten*.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gould returned to America in 1848 and from 1852 to 1867 worked in the United States Coast Survey, where he worked in geodetic astronomy and was in charge of the longitude department.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He developed and organized the service, was one of the first to determine longitudes by telegraphic means, and employed the Atlantic cable in 1866 to establish accurate longitude-relations between Europe and America.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] One of his assistants and life-long mentee was Seth Carlo Chandler, who went on to discover the Chandler wobble.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] After his return to Cambridge, Massachusetts, Gould started the *Astronomical Journal* in 1849, which he published until 1861.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He resumed publication in 1885 and it is still published today.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] From 1855 to 1859 he acted as director of the Dudley Observatory at Albany, New York, and in 1859 published a discussion of the places and proper motions of circumpolar stars to be used as standards by the United States Coast Survey.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1861 he undertook the enormous task of preparing for publication the records of astronomical observations made at the United States Naval Observatory since 1850.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1851 Gould suggested numbering asteroids in their order of discovery, and placing this number in a disk (circle) as the generic symbol of an asteroid.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] That same year, he was elected as a member to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1864 he was admitted to the Massachusetts Society of the Cincinnati to represent his grandfather Captain Benjamin Gould.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In the 1890s he became an early member of the Massachusetts Society of the Sons of the American Revolution.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Appointed in 1862 actuary to the United States Sanitary Commission, he issued in 1869 an important volume of *Investigations in the Military and Anthropological Statistics of American Soldiers*.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] This study, informed by Gould's commitment to race science, purported to construct typologies of Black and Indigenous bodies, in particular.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1864 he fitted up a private observatory at Cambridge, Massachusetts, and undertook in 1868, on behalf of the Argentine republic, to organize a national observatory at Córdoba.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1871 he became the first director of the Argentine National Observatory (today, Observatorio Astronómico de Córdoba of the National University of Córdoba).
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] While there, he and four assistants (including Miles Rock) extensively mapped the southern hemisphere skies using newly developed photometric methods.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] On June 1, 1884, he made the last definite sighting of the Great Comet of 1882.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The need of astronomers for good weather prediction spurred Gould to collaborate with Argentine colleagues to develop the Argentine National Weather Service, the first in South America.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Rutherfurd's photographs of the Pleiades in 1866 entitle him to rank as a pioneer in the use of the camera as an instrument of precision; and he secured at Córdoba 1400 negatives of southern star clusters, the reduction of which occupied the closing years of his life.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He remained in Argentina until 1885, when he returned to Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He received the Gold Medal of the Royal Astronomical Society in 1883 and the James Craig Watson Medal in 1887.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Astronomers continue to investigate the astrophysics of a large scale feature of the Milky Way to which he called their attention in 1877, and honor him with its name, The Gould Belt.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] A crater on the Moon is named after him.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gould was elected a member of the American Antiquarian Society in 1892.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He died at Cambridge, Massachusetts in 1896.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1874, while in Argentina with his assistants, Gould completed his greatest work, the *Uranometria Argentina*, consisting of an atlas published in 1877 and catalog in 1879, for which he received in 1883 the gold medal of the Royal Astronomical Society.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The atlas introduced the system of defining constellation boundaries along lines of right ascension and declination, which was officially adopted by the International Astronomical Union for the whole sky in 1930.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The catalog assigned Gould designations to all bright stars within 100 degrees of the south celestial pole in a manner similar to what Flamsteed had earlier done for the northern hemisphere.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] An updated version, to which late 20th century data have been appended to the complete information for all stars in the original Uranometria Argentina, is available at www.uranometriaargentina.com/.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gould followed his *Uranometria Argentina* with a zone-catalogue of 73,160 stars (1884), and a general catalogue (1885) compiled from meridian observations of 32,448 stars.
[src:alice-bache-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Alice Bache Gould (1868–1953), a mathematician, philanthropist, and historian, was one of his five children.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston was founded on Shawmut Peninsula in 1630 by English Puritan settlers, who named the city after the market town of Boston, Lincolnshire, in England.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] During the American Revolution and Revolutionary War, Boston was home to several seminal events, including the Boston Massacre (1770), the Boston Tea Party (1773), Paul Revere's midnight ride (1775), the Battle of Bunker Hill (1775), and the Siege of Boston (1775–1776).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Following American independence from Great Britain, Boston played an important national role as a port, manufacturing hub, and education and culture center, and the city expanded significantly beyond the original peninsula by filling in land and annexing neighboring towns.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston's many firsts include the nation's first public park (Boston Common, 1634), the first public school (Boston Latin School, 1635), and the first subway system (Tremont Street subway, 1897).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston later emerged as a global leader in higher education and research and was the largest biotechnology hub in the world as of 2023.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The city is a national leader in scientific research, law, medicine, engineering, and business.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] With nearly 5,000 startup companies, the city is considered a global pioneer in innovation, entrepreneurship, and artificial intelligence.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston's economy is led by finance, professional and business services, information technology, and government.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The city's businesses and institutions rank among the top in the nation for environmental sustainability and new investment.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The name of the English town derives from its patron saint, St.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Botolph, in whose church Cotton served as the rector until he and Johnson emigrated to New England.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In early sources, Lincolnshire's Boston was known as "St.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Botolph's town", which was later abbreviated as "Boston".
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Before this renaming, the settlement on the peninsula was known as "Shawmut" by William Blaxton and "Tremontaine" by the Puritan settlers he invited.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Before European colonization, the region surrounding present-day Boston was inhabited by the Massachusett people, who established small, seasonal communities in present-day Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 1630, settlers led by John Winthrop arrived, and found Shawmut Peninsula nearly empty of Native people.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Most had died of European diseases borne by earlier settlers and traders.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Archaeological excavations have unearthed one of the oldest fishweirs in New England, located on Boylston Street, which Native people constructed as early as 7,000 years before European arrival in the Western Hemisphere.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The first European to live in what would become Boston was a University of Cambridge-educated Anglican cleric named William Blaxton.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] He was most directly responsible for the foundation of Boston by Puritan colonists in 1630, after Blaxton invited one of their leaders, Isaac Johnson, to cross Back Bay from the failing colony of Charlestown and share the peninsula with him.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In September 1630 Puritans made the crossing to present-day Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Puritan influence on Boston began even before the settlement was founded with the 1629 Cambridge Agreement, which created the Massachusetts Bay Colony and was signed by the colony's first governor, John Winthrop.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Puritan ethics and their focus on education also influenced the city's early history.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 1635, America's first public school, Boston Latin School, was founded in Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston was the largest town in the Thirteen Colonies until Philadelphia outgrew it in the mid-18th century.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston's oceanfront location made it a lively port, and the town engaged in shipping and fishing during the colonial era.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston was a primary stop on the Caribbean trade route and imported large amounts of molasses, which led to the creation of Boston baked beans.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston's economy stagnated in the decades prior to the American Revolution.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] By the mid-18th century, New York City and Philadelphia both surpassed Boston in wealth.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] During this period, Boston encountered financial difficulties even as other New England cities were growing rapidly.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] , about the British army's decision to leave Boston, dated March 21, 1776.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston played a central role in the American Revolution.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Many crucial events of the American Revolution and subsequent American Revolutionary War occurred in or near Boston, where the city's revolutionary spirit against Britain's colonial governance was demonstrable and ultimately inspiring to the rest of the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] When the British Parliament passed the Stamp Act in 1765, the homes of Andrew Oliver, the official tasked with enforcing the Act, and Thomas Hutchinson, then lieutenant governor of Massachusetts Bay Colony, were raved by Boston mobs.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The British responded by sending two regiments to Boston in 1768 in an attempt to quell the revolt, but the increased British military presence in Boston only ended up further inflaming the Boston colonists.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 1770, during the Boston Massacre, British troops fired into a Boston mob that was protesting their presence.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The massacre forced the British to withdraw their troops and helped fuel revolutionary sentiment in the colonies.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In May 1773, Parliament passed the Tea Act, which many colonists saw as a British attempt to compel them to accept taxes established by the Townshend Acts.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] This led to the Boston Tea Party, a defining event of the American Revolution in which angered Bostonians threw an entire shipment of tea sent from the East India Company into Boston Harbor, escalating the American Revolution.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The British monarchy responded furiously, implementing the Intolerable Acts and demanding compensation for the tea destroyed during the Boston Tea Party.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] This response, in turn, angered the colonists further, leading to the Battles of Lexington and Concord on April 19, 1775, the first battles of the American Revolutionary War, which were fought around Boston in Massachusetts Bay Colony.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] During the siege of Boston from April 19, 1775, to March 17, 1776, New England-based Patriot militia impeded movement by the British Army.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Sir William Howe, then commander-in-chief of British forces in North America, led the British army in the siege.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] On June 17, the British captured Charlestown in present-day Boston during the Battle of Bunker Hill during which the British Army outnumbered Patriot militia.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] But the British sustained irreplaceable casualties, turning the Battle of Bunker Hill into a pyrrhic victory for the British.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The Battle of Bunker Hill also demonstrated the skill and training of the Patriot militia, whose stubborn defense made it difficult for the British to capture Charlestown without suffering even further casualties.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] On June 14, 1775, in an effort to unify the Revolutionary War effort, the Second Continental Congress, convening in the colonial-era capital of Philadelphia, founded the Continental Army and unanimously appointed George Washington as its commander-in-chief.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Washington then immediately departed Philadelphia for Boston, where he arrived on July 2, 1775, and led the newly-formed Continental Army in the siege.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Fighting was limited to small-scale raids and skirmishes, and the Continental Army faced challenges with a deficiency of munitions and supplies.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston Neck, then narrow and only approximately 100 feet wide, impeded Washington's ability to invade Boston, which led to a prolonged stalemate between the Continental Army and British forces.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] A young officer, Rufus Putnam, came up with a plan to make portable fortifications out of wood, which were erected on the frozen ground under cover of darkness.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Putnam supervised the effort, which successfully installed the fortifications and dozens of cannons on Dorchester Heights that Henry Knox laboriously brought through the snow from Fort Ticonderoga.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The following morning, the astonished British Army awoke to see a large array of cannons bearing down on them.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] General Howe is believed to have said that the Americans had done more in one night than his British Army could have done in six months.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The British Army responded by attempting to launch a cannon barrage for two hours, but their shots could not reach the Continental Army's cannons at such a height.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The British then gave up, boarded their ships, and sailed away from Boston in what has come to be known as "Evacuation Day", which is now celebrated in Boston annually on March 17.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] After the British retreat, Washington was so impressed with the effort of Rufus Putnam that he appointed him as his chief engineer.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] After the Revolution, Boston's long seafaring tradition helped make it one of the nation's busiest ports for both domestic and international trade.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston's harbor activity was significantly curtailed by the Embargo Act of 1807, which was adopted during the Napoleonic Wars, and the War of 1812.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Foreign trade returned after these hostilities, but Boston's merchants had found alternatives for their capital investments in the meantime.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Manufacturing became an important component of the city's economy, and the city's industrial manufacturing overtook international trade in economic importance by the mid-19th century.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The small rivers bordering the city and connecting it to the surrounding region facilitated shipment of goods and led to a proliferation of mills and factories.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Later, a dense network of railroads furthered the region's industry and commerce.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] During this period, Boston also flourished culturally.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] It was admired for its rarefied literary life and generous artistic patronage.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Members of old Boston families, later dubbed "Boston Brahmins", came to be regarded as the nation's social and cultural elites.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] They are often associated with the American upper class, Harvard University, and the Episcopal Church.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston was a prominent port of the Atlantic slave trade in the New England Colonies, but was soon overtaken by Salem, Massachusetts, and Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston eventually became a center of the American abolitionist movement.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The city reacted largely negatively to the Fugitive Slave Act of 1850, contributing to President Franklin Pierce's attempt to make an example of Boston after Anthony Burns's attempt to escape to freedom.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 1822, the citizens of Boston voted to change the official name from the "Town of Boston" to the "City of Boston", and on March 19, 1822, the people of Boston accepted the charter incorporating the city.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] At the time Boston was chartered as a city, the population was about 46,226, while the area of the city was only 4.8 sq mi (12 km2).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In the 1820s, Boston's population grew rapidly, and the city's ethnic composition changed dramatically with the first wave of European immigrants.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Irish immigrants dominated the first wave of newcomers during this period, especially following the Great Famine; by 1850, about 35,000 Irish lived in Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In the latter half of the 19th century, the city saw increasing numbers of Irish, Germans, Lebanese, Syrians, French Canadians, and Russian and Polish Jews settling there.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] By the end of the 19th century, Boston's core neighborhoods had become enclaves of ethnically distinct immigrants with their residence yielding lasting cultural change.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Italians became the largest inhabitants of the North End, Irish dominated South Boston and Charlestown, and Russian Jews lived in the West End.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Irish and Italian immigrants brought with them Roman Catholicism.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Currently, Catholics make up Boston's largest religious community, and the Irish have played a major role in Boston politics since the early 20th century; prominent figures include the Kennedys, Tip O'Neill, and John F.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Between 1631 and 1890, the city tripled its area through land reclamation by filling in marshes, mud flats, and gaps between wharves along the waterfront.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Reclamation projects in the middle of the 19th century created significant parts of the South End, the West End, the Financial District, and Chinatown.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] After the Great Boston Fire of 1872, workers used building rubble as landfill along the downtown waterfront.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] During the mid-to-late 19th century, workers filled almost 600 acres (240 ha) of brackish Charles River marshlands west of Boston Common with gravel brought by rail from the hills of Needham Heights.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Other proposals were unsuccessful for the annexation of Brookline, Cambridge, and Chelsea.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Many architecturally significant buildings were built during the early years of the 20th century: Horticultural Hall, the Tennis and Racquet Club, Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum, Fenway Studios, Jordan Hall, and the Boston Opera House.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The Longfellow Bridge, built in 1906, was mentioned by Robert McCloskey in *Make Way for Ducklings*, describing its "salt and pepper shakers" feature.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Fenway Park, home of the Boston Red Sox, opened in 1912, with the Boston Garden opening in 1928.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Logan International Airport opened on September 8, 1923.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] On November 28, 1942, Boston's Cocoanut Grove nightclub was the site of the Cocoanut Grove fire, the deadliest nightclub fire in United States history, killing 492 people and injuring hundreds more.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] By the early- to mid-20th century, Boston declined economically as factories became old and obsolete and businesses moved out of the region for cheaper labor elsewhere.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston responded by initiating various urban renewal projects, under the direction of the Boston Redevelopment Authority (BRA) established in 1957.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 1958, BRA initiated a project to improve the historic West End neighborhood.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Extensive demolition was met with strong public opposition, and thousands of families were displaced.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The BRA continued implementing eminent domain projects, including the clearance of the vibrant Scollay Square area for construction of the modernist style Government Center.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 1965, the Columbia Point Health Center opened in the Dorchester neighborhood, the first Community Health Center in the United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] It mostly served the massive Columbia Point public housing complex adjoining it, which was built in 1953.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The health center is still in operation and was rededicated in 1990 as the Geiger-Gibson Community Health Center.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The Columbia Point complex itself was redeveloped and revitalized from 1984 to 1990 into a mixed-income residential development called Harbor Point Apartments.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] By the 1970s, the city's economy had begun to recover after 30 years of economic downturn.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] A large number of high-rises were constructed in the Financial District and in Boston's Back Bay during this period.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] This boom continued into the mid-1980s and resumed after a few pauses.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Hospitals such as Massachusetts General Hospital, Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, and Brigham and Women's Hospital lead the nation in medical innovation and patient care.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Nevertheless, the city experienced conflict starting in 1974 over desegregation busing, which resulted in unrest and violence around public schools throughout the mid-1970s.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston has also experienced gentrification in the latter half of the 20th century, with housing prices increasing sharply since the 1990s when the city's rent control regime was struck down by statewide ballot proposition.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston is an intellectual, technological, and political center.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] However, it has lost some important regional institutions, including the loss to mergers and acquisitions of local financial institutions such as FleetBoston Financial, which was acquired by Charlotte-based Bank of America in 2004.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston-based department stores Jordan Marsh and Filene's have both merged into the New York City–based Macy's.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The 1993 acquisition of *The Boston Globe* by *The New York Times* was reversed in 2013 when it was resold to Boston businessman John W.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 2016, it was announced General Electric would be moving its corporate headquarters from Connecticut to the Seaport District in Boston, joining many other companies in this rapidly developing neighborhood.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The city also saw the completion of the Central Artery/Tunnel Project, known as the Big Dig, in 2007 after many delays and cost overruns.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] On April 15, 2013, two Chechen Islamist brothers detonated a pair of bombs near the finish line of the Boston Marathon, killing three people and injuring roughly 264.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The subsequent search for the bombers led to a lock-down of Boston and surrounding municipalities.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The region showed solidarity during this time as symbolized by the slogan *Boston Strong*.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 2016, Boston briefly shouldered a bid as the U.S. applicant for the 2024 Summer Olympics.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The bid was supported by the mayor and a coalition of business leaders and local philanthropists, but was eventually dropped due to public opposition.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The USOC then selected Los Angeles to be the American candidate with Los Angeles ultimately securing the right to host the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Nevertheless, Boston is one of eleven U.S. cities which will host matches during the 2026 FIFA World Cup, with games taking place at Gillette Stadium.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The city's elevation, as measured at Logan International Airport, is 19 ft (5.8 m) above sea level.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The highest point in Boston is Bellevue Hill at 330 ft (100 m) above sea level, and the lowest point is at sea level.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The city is adjacent to Boston Harbor, an arm of Massachusetts Bay, and by extension, the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston is surrounded by the Greater Boston metropolitan region.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The Charles River separates Boston's Allston-Brighton, Fenway-Kenmore and Back Bay neighborhoods from Watertown and Cambridge, and most of Boston from its own Charlestown neighborhood.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The Neponset River forms the boundary between Boston's southern neighborhoods and Quincy and Milton.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The Mystic River separates Charlestown from Chelsea and Everett, and Chelsea Creek and Boston Harbor separate East Boston from Downtown, the North End, and the Seaport.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston is sometimes called a "city of neighborhoods" because of the profusion of diverse subsections.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] More than two-thirds of inner Boston's modern land area did not exist when the city was founded.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Instead, it was created via the gradual filling in of the surrounding tidal areas over the centuries.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] This was accomplished using earth from the leveling or lowering of Boston's three original hills, the "Trimountain", after which Tremont Street is named, and with gravel brought by train from Needham to fill the Back Bay.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Back Bay is home to Christian Science Center, Copley Square, Newbury Street, and New England's two tallest buildings: the John Hancock Tower and the Prudential Center.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Near the John Hancock Tower is the old John Hancock Building with its prominent illuminated beacon, the color of which forecasts the weather.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Downtown and its immediate surroundings (including the Financial District, Government Center, and South Boston) consist largely of low-rise masonry buildings – often federal style and Greek revival – interspersed with modern high-rises.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Back Bay includes many prominent landmarks, such as the Boston Public Library, Trinity Church, single-family homes and wooden/brick multi-family row houses.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The South End Historic District is the largest surviving contiguous Victorian-era neighborhood in the US.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The geography of downtown and South Boston was particularly affected by the Central Artery/Tunnel Project (which ran from 1991 to 2007, and was known unofficially as the "Big Dig").
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] That project removed the elevated Central Artery and incorporated new green spaces and open areas.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston is located within the Boston Basin ecoregion, which is characterized by low and rolling hills with a number of ponds, lakes, and reservoirs.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Forests are mainly transition hardwoods such as oak-hickory mixed with white pine.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] As a coastal city built largely on fill, sea-level rise is of major concern to the city government.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] A climate action plan from 2019 anticipates 2 ft (1 m) to more than 7 ft (2 m) of sea-level rise in Boston by the end of the 21st century.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Many older buildings in certain areas of Boston are supported by wooden piles driven into the area's fill; these piles remain sound if submerged in water, but are subject to dry rot if exposed to air for long periods.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Groundwater levels have been dropping in many areas of the city, due in part to an increase in the amount of rainwater discharged directly into sewers rather than absorbed by the ground.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The Boston Groundwater Trust coordinates monitoring groundwater levels throughout the city via a network of public and private monitoring wells.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The city developed a climate action plan covering carbon reduction in buildings, transportation, and energy use.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The first such plan was commissioned in 2007, with updates released in 2011, 2014, and 2019.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] This plan includes the Building Energy Reporting and Disclosure Ordinance, which requires the city's larger buildings to disclose their yearly energy and water use statistics and to partake in an energy assessment every five years.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] A separate initiative, Resilient Boston Harbor, lays out neighborhood-specific recommendations for coastal resilience.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 2013, Mayor Thomas Menino introduced the Renew Boston Whole Building Incentive which reduces the cost of living in buildings that are deemed energy efficient.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Under the Köppen climate classification (using the −3 °C (27 °F) coldest month isotherm), Boston has ahumid subtropical climate (Köppen *Cfa*)..
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] If using the 0 °C (32 °F) coldest month isotherm, the city lies within the hot-summer humid continental zone (Köppen *Dfa*).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Winters are cold and stormy, with occasional periods of heavy snow.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Spring and fall are usually cool and mild, with varying conditions dependent on wind direction and the position of the jet stream.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Prevailing wind patterns that blow offshore minimize the influence of the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In winter, areas near the immediate coast often see more rain than snow, as warm air is sometimes drawn off the Atlantic.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston lies at the border between USDA plant hardiness zones 6b (away from the coastline) and 7a (close to the coastline).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Receiving over 2,600 hours of sunshine annually, Boston is one of the sunniest oceanic cities located at its latitude globally.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The warmest month is July, with a mean temperature of 74.1 °F (23.4 °C).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The coldest month is January, with a mean temperature of 29.9 °F (−1.2 °C).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Periods exceeding 90 °F (32 °C) in summer and below freezing in winter are not uncommon but tend to be fairly short, with about 13 and 25 days per year seeing each, respectively.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Despite average winter temperatures near freezing, Boston can see entire winters without sustained periods of sub-freezing afternoons.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The winter of 2001-2002 recorded only two days entirely below freezing, with no day with a daily maximum temperature below 29 °F (−2 °C).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The winter of 2023-2024 saw the yearly minimum temperature not falling below 14 °F (−10 °C) that winter.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Sub- 0 °F (−18 °C) readings usually occur every 3 to 5 years.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The most recent sub- 0 °F (−18 °C) reading occurred on February 4, 2023, when the temperature dipped down to −10 °F (−23 °C).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] This was the lowest temperature reading in Boston since 1957.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Several decades may pass between 100 °F (38 °C) readings.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The last such reading occurred on June 24, 2025.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston's average window for freezing temperatures is November 9 to April 5.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Official temperature records have ranged from −18 °F (−28 °C) on February 9, 1934, up to 104 °F (40 °C) on July 4, 1911.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The record cold daily maximum is 2 °F (−17 °C) on December 30, 1917.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The record warm daily minimum is 83 °F (28 °C) on both August 2, 1975, and July 21, 2019.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The record high dew point is 79 °F (26 °C) recorded on August 10, 2001.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The most humid month on record is August 2018 with an average dewpoint of 66.8 °F (19.3 °C) for the month.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The hottest month on record is July 2019 with an average mean temperature of 78.7 °F (25.9 °C) for the month.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The month with the record warmest daily minimums was July 2019 with an average daily minimum of 70.7 °F (21.5 °C).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston has recorded entire months in summer without nighttime lows below 63 °F (17 °C), the record most recently tied in August 2022 and previously set in July 2011 and July 2019.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Summer in Boston can also see entire months without dewpoints below 53 °F (12 °C), with the most recent occurrence being July 2008.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston has not recorded a summer since records began without at least one daily minimum of at least 69 °F (21 °C) or higher, and a dewpoint of 71 °F (22 °C) or greater.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The summers where the yearly maximum dew point topped out at 71 °F (22 °C) were in 1974 and 1982; and the yearly maximum daily minimum temperature at 69 °F (21 °C) in 1889.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The average yearly maximum daily minimum temperature is 76.9 °F (24.9 °C), and the average yearly maximum dew point is 75.4 °F (24.1 °C).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston averages 43.6 in (1,110 mm) of precipitation a year, with 49.2 in (125 cm) of snowfall per season.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Most snowfall occurs from mid-November to early April.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] There is high year-to-year variability in snowfall.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] For instance, the winter of 2011–12 saw only 9.3 in (23.6 cm) of accumulating snow, but the previous winter, the corresponding figure was 81.0 in (206 cm).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston's coastal location on the North Atlantic makes the city very prone to nor'easters, which can produce large amounts of snow and rain.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Fog is relatively common, particularly in spring and early summer.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Due to its coastal location, Boston often receives sea breezes, especially in the late spring, when water temperatures are still quite cold and temperatures at the coast can be more than 20 °F (11 °C) colder than a few miles inland, sometimes dropping by that amount near midday.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Thunderstorms typically occur from May to September.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Occasionally, they can become severe, with large hail, damaging winds, and heavy downpours.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Although downtown Boston has never been struck by a violent tornado, Boston has experienced many tornado warnings.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Damaging storms are more common to areas north, west, and northwest of the city.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In the 2020 census, Boston was estimated to have 691,531 residents living in 266,724 households—a 12% population increase over 2010.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston is the third-most densely populated large U.S. city of over half a million residents, and the most densely populated state capital.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Some 1.2 million persons may be within Boston's boundaries during work hours, and as many as 2 million during special events.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] This fluctuation of people is caused by hundreds of thousands of suburban residents who travel to the city for work, education, health care, and special events.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] For every 100 females, there were 92.0 males.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 89.9 males.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] There were 252,699 households, of which 20.4% had children under the age of 18 living in them, 25.5% were married couples living together, 16.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 54.0% were non-families.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] 37.1% of all households were made up of individuals, and 9.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The average household size was 2.26 and the average family size was 3.08.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 2024, the median household income in Boston was $97,791, while the median income for a family was $110,710.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 2011, full-time year-round male workers had a median income of $52,544 versus $46,540 for full-time year-round female workers.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The per capita income for the city was $33,158.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] 21.4% of the population and 16.0% of families were below the poverty line.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Of the total population, 28.8% of those under the age of 18 and 20.4% of those 65 and older were living below the poverty line.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Boston has a significant racial wealth gap with White Bostonians having a median net worth of $247,500 compared to an $8 median net worth for non-immigrant Black residents and $0 for Dominican immigrant residents.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] From the 1950s to the end of the 20th century, the proportion of non-Hispanic Whites in Boston declined.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 2000, non-Hispanic Whites were 49.5% of Boston's population, making the city majority minority for the first time.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In the 21st century, Boston has experienced significant gentrification, during which affluent Whites have moved into formerly non-White areas.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Census Bureau estimated non-Hispanic Whites again formed a slight majority.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] By 2010, in part due to a crash in housing prices, as well as increased efforts to make affordable housing more available, the non-White population had rebounded and non-Hispanic White residents formed 47% of the population.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] constitute the largest ethnicity in Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 2011, African-Americans comprised 22% of the city's population.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] People of Irish descent formed the second-largest single ethnic group in the city, making up 15.8% of the population, followed by Italians, accounting for 8.3% of the population.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] People of West Indian and Caribbean ancestry are another sizable group, collectively at over 15%.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In Greater Boston, these numbers grew significantly, with 150,000 Dominicans according to 2018 estimates, 134,000 Puerto Ricans, 57,500 Salvadorans, 39,000 Guatemalans, 36,000 Mexicans, and over 35,000 Colombians.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] East Boston has a diverse Hispanic/Latino population of Salvadorans, Colombians, Guatemalans, Mexicans, Dominicans and Puerto Ricans.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Hispanic populations in southwest Boston neighborhoods are mainly made up of Dominicans and Puerto Ricans, usually sharing neighborhoods in this section with African Americans and Blacks with origins from the Caribbean and Africa especially Cape Verdeans and Haitians.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Neighborhoods such as Jamaica Plain and Roslindale have a growing number of Dominican Americans.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] There is a large and historical Armenian community in Boston, and the city is home to the Armenian Heritage Park.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Over 27,000 Chinese Americans made their home in Boston city proper in 2013.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] Data is from the American Community Survey's five-year estimates 2008–2012.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In a 2023-24 study by the Pew Research Center, 47% of the population of the city identified themselves as Christians, with 21% attending a variety of Protestant churches and 24% professing Roman Catholic beliefs.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The remaining 13% are composed of adherents of Judaism, Buddhism, Islam, Hinduism, and other faiths.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 2010, the Catholic Church had the highest number of adherents as a single denomination in the Greater Boston area, with more than two million members and 339 churches, followed by the Episcopal Church with 58,000 adherents in 160 churches.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] The United Church of Christ had 55,000 members and 213 churches.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] In 2015, the Boston metro area had a Jewish population of approximately 248,000.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] More than half the Jewish households in the Greater Boston area reside in the city itself, Brookline, Newton, Cambridge, Somerville, or adjacent towns.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p01] A small minority practices Confucianism, and some practice Boston Confucianism, an American evolution of Confucianism adapted for Boston intellectuals.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] A global city, Boston is ranked among the top 30 most economically powerful cities in the world.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Encompassing $610 billion, the Greater Boston metropolitan area has the eighth-largest economy in the country and 16th-largest in the world.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston's colleges and universities exert a significant impact on the regional economy.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston attracts more than 350,000 college students from around the world, who contribute more than US$4.8 billion annually to the city's economy.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The area's schools are major employers and attract industries to the city and surrounding region.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The city is home to a number of technology companies and is a hub for biotechnology, with the Milken Institute rating Boston as the top life sciences cluster in the country.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston receives the highest absolute amount of annual funding from the National Institutes of Health of all cities in the United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston is considered highly innovative for a variety of reasons, including the presence of academia, access to venture capital, and the presence of many high-tech companies.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Route 128 corridor and Greater Boston continue to be a major center for venture capital investment, and high technology remains an important sector.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Tourism composes a large part of Boston's economy, with 21.2 million domestic and international visitors spending $8.3 billion in 2011.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Excluding visitors from Canada and Mexico, over 1.4 million international tourists visited Boston in 2014, with those from China and the United Kingdom leading the list.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston's status as a state capital as well as the regional home of federal agencies has rendered law and government to be another major component of the city's economy.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston is a major seaport along the East Coast of the United States and the oldest continuously operated industrial and fishing port in the Western Hemisphere.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] In the 2018 Global Financial Centres Index, Boston was ranked as having the 13th-most competitive financial services center in the world and the second-most competitive in the United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston-based Fidelity Investments helped popularize the mutual fund in the 1980s and has made Boston one of the top financial centers in the United States and a center for venture capital firms.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston is home to the headquarters of Santander Bank and State Street Corporation, the latter specializing in asset management and custody services.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston is a printing and publishing center—Houghton Mifflin Harcourt is headquartered within the city, along with Bedford-St.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Pearson PLC publishing units employ several hundred people in Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston is home to two convention centers—the Hynes Convention Center in the Back Bay and the Boston Convention and Exhibition Center on the South Boston waterfront.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston is home to the headquarters of several major athletic and footwear companies including Converse, New Balance, and Reebok.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Rockport, Puma and Wolverine World Wide, Inc. headquarters or regional offices are just outside the city.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston Public Schools enroll 57,000 students attending 145 schools, including Boston Latin Academy, John D.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] O'Bryant School of Math & Science, and the Boston Latin School.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Boston Latin School was established in 1635 and is the oldest public high school in the US.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston also operates the United States' second-oldest public high school and its oldest public elementary school.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The system's students are 40% Hispanic or Latino, 35% Black or African American, 13% White, and 9% Asian.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] There are private, parochial, and charter schools.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Approximately 3,300 minority students attend participating suburban schools through the Metropolitan Educational Opportunity Council.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] In September 2019, the city began Boston Saves, a program that provides every child enrolled in the city's kindergarten system a savings account, containing $50 to be used toward college or career training.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Several of the highest-ranked universities in the world are near Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Three universities with a major presence in the city, Harvard, MIT, and Tufts, are just outside of Boston in the cities of Cambridge and Somerville, known as the *Brainpower Triangle*.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Harvard is the nation's oldest institute of higher education and is centered across the Charles River in Cambridge, though the majority of its land holdings and a substantial amount of its educational activities are in Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Its business school and athletics facilities are in Boston's Allston neighborhood, and its medical, dental, and public health schools are located in the Longwood area.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) originated in Boston and was long known as "Boston Tech"; it moved across the river to Cambridge in 1916.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Tufts University's main campus is north of the city in Somerville and Medford, though its medical and dental schools are located in Boston's Chinatown at Tufts Medical Center.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Greater Boston has more than 50 colleges and universities, with 250,000 students enrolled in Boston and Cambridge alone.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston's only public university is the University of Massachusetts Boston on Columbia Point in Dorchester.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Roxbury Community College and Bunker Hill Community College are the city's two public community colleges.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Altogether, Boston's colleges and universities employ more than 42,600 people, accounting for nearly seven percent of the city's workforce.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Five members of the Association of American Universities are in Greater Boston, more than any other metropolitan area: Harvard University, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Tufts University, Boston University, and Brandeis University.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Greater Boston contains seven Highest Research Activity (R1) Universities as per the Carnegie Classification.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] This includes, in addition to the aforementioned five, Boston College, and Northeastern University.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] This is, by a large margin, the highest concentration of such institutions in a single metropolitan area.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Hospitals, universities, and research institutions in Greater Boston received more than $1.77 billion in National Institutes of Health grants in 2013, more money than any other American metropolitan area.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] This high density of research institutes also contributes to Boston's high density of early career researchers, which, due to high housing costs in the region, have been shown to face housing stress.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The region is home to several conservatories and art schools, including the New England Conservatory (the oldest independent conservatory in the United States), the Boston Conservatory, and Berklee College of Music, which has made Boston an important city for jazz music.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Many trade schools also exist in the city such as the Boston Career Institute, the North Bennet Street School, and Greater Boston Joint Apprentice Training Center.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston has a strong mayor–council government system in which the mayor, elected every fourth year, has extensive executive power.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Michelle Wu became mayor in November 2021, succeeding Kim Janey who became the Acting Mayor in March 2021 following Marty Walsh's confirmation to the position of Secretary of Labor in the Biden/Harris Administration.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Walsh's predecessor Thomas Menino's twenty-year tenure was the longest in Boston's history.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Boston City Council is elected every two years.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] There are nine district seats, and four citywide "at-large" seats.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The School Committee, which oversees the Boston Public Schools, is appointed by the mayor.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston uses an algorithm called CityScore to measure the effectiveness of city services.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] This score is available on a public online dashboard and allows city managers in police, fire, schools, emergency management services, and 3-1-1 to take action and make adjustments in areas of concern.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] As the capital of Massachusetts, Boston plays a major role in state politics.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston has several federal facilities, including the John F.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Kennedy Federal Office Building, the Thomas P.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] McCormack Post Office and Courthouse, and the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit and the United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts are housed in The John Joseph Moakley United States Courthouse.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Federally, Boston is split between two congressional districts.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Three-fourths of Boston is in the 7th district and is represented by Ayanna Pressley.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The remaining southern fourth is in the 8th district and is represented by Stephen Lynch.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Both are Democrats; a Republican has not represented a significant portion of Boston in over a century.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The state's senior member of the United States Senate is Democrat Elizabeth Warren, first elected in 2012.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The state's junior member of the United States Senate is Democrat Ed Markey, who was elected in 2013 to succeed John Kerry after Kerry's appointment and confirmation as the United States Secretary of State.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston included $414 million in spending on the Boston Police Department in the fiscal 2021 budget.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] This is the second largest allocation of funding by the city after the allocation to Boston Public Schools.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Like many major American cities, Boston has experienced a great reduction in violent crime since the early 1990s.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston's low crime rate since the 1990s has been credited to the Boston Police Department's collaboration with neighborhood groups and church parishes to prevent youths from joining gangs, as well as involvement from the United States Attorney and District Attorney's offices.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] This helped lead in part to what has been touted as the "Boston Miracle".
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Murders in Boston dropped from 152 in 1990, a murder rate of 26.5 per 100,000 people, to 31—not one of them a juvenile—in 1999, for a murder rate of 5.26 per 100,000.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] According to the Uniform Crime Reporting (UCR) program in 2022, Boston had 3,955 reported violent crimes, which include homicide, rape, robbery, and aggravated assault, and 11,514 reported property crimes, which include arson, burglary, larceny-theft, and motor vehicle theft.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] With a violent crime rate of 608.7 per 100,000 people, the city's violent crime rate is higher than Massachusetts' rate of 322 per 100,000 people and the national rate of 380.7 per 100,000 people.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] While Boston's property crime rate, at 1,772.0 per 100,000 people, is higher than Massachusetts' property crime rate of 1,070.1 per 100,000 people, it is lower than the national property crime rate of 1,954.4 per 100,000 people.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston shares many cultural roots with greater New England, including a dialect of the non-rhotic Eastern New England accent known as the Boston accent and a regional cuisine with a large emphasis on seafood, salt, and dairy products.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston also has its own collection of neologisms known as *Boston slang* and sardonic humor.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] In the early 1800s, William Tudor wrote that Boston was "'perhaps the most perfect and certainly the best-regulated democracy that ever existed.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] In the 19th century, Ralph Waldo Emerson, Henry David Thoreau, Nathaniel Hawthorne, Margaret Fuller, James Russell Lowell, and Henry Wadsworth Longfellow wrote in Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Some consider the Old Corner Bookstore to be the "cradle of American literature", the place where these writers met and where *The Atlantic Monthly* was first published.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] In 1852, the Boston Public Library was founded as the first free library in the United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston's literary culture continues today thanks to the city's many universities and the Boston Book Festival.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Music is afforded a high degree of civic support in Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Boston Symphony Orchestra is one of the "Big Five", a group of the greatest American orchestras, and the classical music magazine *Gramophone* called it one of the "world's best" orchestras.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Symphony Hall (west of Back Bay) is home to the Boston Symphony Orchestra and the related Boston Youth Symphony Orchestra, which is the largest youth orchestra in the nation, and to the Boston Pops Orchestra.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Other concerts are held at the New England Conservatory's Jordan Hall.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Boston Ballet performs at the Boston Opera House.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Other performing-arts organizations in the city include the Boston Lyric Opera Company, Opera Boston, Boston Baroque (the first permanent Baroque orchestra in the US), and the Handel and Haydn Society (one of the oldest choral companies in the United States).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston is a center for contemporary classical music with a number of performing groups, several of which are associated with the city's conservatories and universities.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] These include the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Boston Musica Viva.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Several theaters are in or near the Theater District south of Boston Common, including the Cutler Majestic Theatre, Citi Performing Arts Center, the Colonial Theater, and the Orpheum Theatre.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The city is the site of several events during the Fourth of July period.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] They include the week-long Harborfest festivities and a Boston Pops concert accompanied by fireworks on the banks of the Charles River.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Several historic sites relating to the American Revolution period are preserved as part of the Boston National Historical Park because of the city's prominent role.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Many are found along the Freedom Trail, which is marked by a red line of bricks embedded in the ground.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The city is home to several art museums and galleries, including the Museum of Fine Arts and Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Institute of Contemporary Art is housed in a contemporary building designed by Diller Scofidio + Renfro in the Seaport District.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston's South End Art and Design District (SoWa) and Newbury St. are both art gallery destinations.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Columbia Point is the location of the University of Massachusetts Boston, the Edward M.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Kennedy Institute for the United States Senate, the John F.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum, and the Massachusetts Archives and Commonwealth Museum.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Boston Athenæum (one of the oldest independent libraries in the United States), Boston Children's Museum, Bull & Finch Pub (whose building is known from the television show *Cheers*), Museum of Science, and the New England Aquarium are within the city.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston has been a noted religious center from its earliest days.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Boston serves nearly 300 parishes and is based in the Cathedral of the Holy Cross (1875) in the South End, while the Episcopal Diocese of Massachusetts serves just under 200 congregations, with the Cathedral Church of St.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Unitarian Universalism has its headquarters in the Fort Point neighborhood.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Christian Scientists are headquartered in Back Bay at the Mother Church (1894).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The oldest church in Boston is First Church in Boston, founded in 1630.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] King's Chapel was the city's first Anglican church, founded in 1686 and converted to Unitarianism in 1785.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Other churches include Old South Church (1669), Christ Church (better known as Old North Church, 1723), the oldest church building in the city, Trinity Church (1733), Park Street Church (1809), and Basilica and Shrine of Our Lady of Perpetual Help on Mission Hill (1878).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston has teams in the four major North American men's professional sports leagues plus Major League Soccer.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] As of 2024, the city has won 40 championships in these leagues.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Boston Red Sox, a founding member of the American League of Major League Baseball in 1901, play their home games at Fenway Park, near Kenmore Square, in the city's Fenway section.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Built in 1912, it is the oldest sports arena or stadium in active use in the United States among the four major professional American sports leagues, Major League Baseball, the National Football League, National Basketball Association, and the National Hockey League.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston was the site of the first game of the first modern World Series, in 1903.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The series was played between the AL Champion Boston Americans and the NL champion Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Persistent reports that the team was known in 1903 as the "Boston Pilgrims" appear to be unfounded.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston's first professional baseball team was the Red Stockings, one of the charter members of the National Association in 1871, and of the National League in 1876.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The team played under that name until 1883, under the name Beaneaters until 1911, and under the name Braves from 1912 until they moved to Milwaukee after the 1952 season.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Since 1966 they have played in Atlanta as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] TD Garden, formerly called the FleetCenter and built to replace the since-demolished Boston Garden, is above North Station and is the home of two major league teams: the Boston Bruins of the National Hockey League and the Boston Celtics of the National Basketball Association.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Bruins were the first American member of the National Hockey League and an Original Six franchise.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Boston Celtics were founding members of the Basketball Association of America, one of the two leagues that merged to form the NBA.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Celtics have won eighteen championships, the most of any NBA team.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] While they have played in suburban Foxborough since 1971, the New England Patriots of the National Football League were founded in 1960 as the Boston Patriots, changing their name after relocating.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] They share Gillette Stadium with the New England Revolution of Major League Soccer.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Another team associated with Boston who plays outside the city is the Boston Fleet of the PWHL, which plays at the Tsongas Center in nearby Lowell.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] During the inaugural 2024 PWHL playoffs, the Fleet (then simply known as PWHL Boston) made it to the Walter Cup finals, where they lost to the Minnesota Frost (PWHL Minnesota at the time).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The area's many colleges and universities are active in college athletics.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Four NCAA Division I members play in the area—Boston College, Boston University, Harvard University, and Northeastern University.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Of the four, only Boston College participates in college football at the highest level, the Football Bowl Subdivision.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Harvard participates in the second-highest level, the Football Championship Subdivision.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] These four universities participate in the Beanpot, an annual men's and women's ice hockey tournament.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The men's Beanpot is hosted at the TD Garden, while the women's Beanpot is held at each member school's home arena on a rotating basis.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston has Esports teams, such as the Overwatch League (OWL)'s Boston Uprising.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Established in 2017, they were the first team to complete a perfect stage with 0 losses.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Boston Breach is another esports team in the Call of Duty League (CDL).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] One of the best-known sporting events in the city is the Boston Marathon, the 26.2 mi (42.2 km) race which is the world's oldest annual marathon, run on Patriots' Day in April.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Red Sox traditionally play a home game starting around 11 a.m. on the same day, with the early start time allowing fans to watch runners finish the race nearby after the conclusion of the ballgame.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Another major annual event is the Head of the Charles Regatta, held in October.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston Common, near the Financial District and Beacon Hill, is the oldest public park in the United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Along with the adjacent Boston Public Garden, it is part of the Emerald Necklace, a string of parks designed by Frederick Law Olmsted to run through the city.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Emerald Necklace includes the Back Bay Fens, Arnold Arboretum, Jamaica Pond, Boston's largest body of freshwater, and Franklin Park, the city's largest park and home of the Franklin Park Zoo.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Another major park is the Esplanade, along the banks of the Charles River.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Hatch Shell, an outdoor concert venue, is adjacent to the Charles River Esplanade.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Other parks are scattered throughout the city, with major parks and beaches near Castle Island and the south end, in Charlestown and along the Dorchester, South Boston, and East Boston shorelines.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston's black community is served by the *Bay State Banner*, a newspaper focused on the issues of interest to black Bostonians.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The *Bay State Banner* has operated since 1965.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The city's growing Latino population has given rise to a number of local and regional Spanish-language newspapers.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] These include *El Planeta* (owned by the former publisher of the *Boston Phoenix*), *El Mundo*, and *La Semana*.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] *Siglo21*, with its main offices in nearby Lawrence, is also widely distributed.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] LGBT publications serve Boston's large LGBT (lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender) population such as *The Rainbow Times*, the only minority and lesbian-owned LGBT news magazine.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Founded in 2006, *The Rainbow Times* is now based out of Boston, but serves all of New England.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston is the largest broadcasting market in New England, with the radio market being the ninth largest in the United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Several major AM stations include talk radio WRKO, sports/talk station WEEI, and news radio WBZ (AM).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] WBZ is a 50,000 watt "clear channel" station whose nighttime broadcasts are heard hundreds of miles from Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] A variety of commercial FM radio formats serve the area, as do NPR stations WBUR and WGBH.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] College and university radio stations include WERS (Emerson), WHRB (Harvard), WUMB (UMass Boston), WMBR (MIT), WZBC (Boston College), WMFO (Tufts University), WBRS (Brandeis University), WRBB (Northeastern University) and WMLN-FM (Curry College).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Boston television DMA, which also includes Manchester, New Hampshire, is the eighth largest in the United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The city is also home to PBS member station WGBH-TV 2, a major producer of PBS programs, which also operates WGBX 44.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Spanish-language television networks, including UniMás (WUTF-TV 27), Telemundo (WNEU 60, a sister station to WBTS-CD), and Univisión (WUNI 66), have a presence in the region, with WNEU and WUNI serving as network owned-and-operated stations.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Most of the area's television stations have their transmitters in nearby Needham and Newton along the Route 128 corridor.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Seven Boston television stations are carried by satellite television and cable television providers in Canada.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Many of Boston's medical facilities are associated with universities.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Longwood Medical and Academic Area, adjacent to the Fenway, district, is home to a large number of medical and research facilities, including Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, Brigham and Women's Hospital, Boston Children's Hospital, Dana–Farber Cancer Institute, and Joslin Diabetes Center.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Prominent medical facilities, including Massachusetts General Hospital, Massachusetts Eye and Ear Infirmary and Spaulding Rehabilitation Hospital are in the Beacon Hill area.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Many of the facilities in Longwood and near Massachusetts General Hospital are affiliated with Harvard Medical School.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Tufts Medical Center (formerly Tufts-New England Medical Center), in the southern portion of the Chinatown neighborhood, is affiliated with Tufts University School of Medicine.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston Medical Center, in the South End neighborhood, is the region's largest safety-net hospital and trauma center.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Formed by the merger of Boston City Hospital, the first municipal hospital in the United States, and Boston University Hospital, Boston Medical Center now serves as the primary teaching facility for the Boston University School of Medicine.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston Medical Center – Brighton (formerly St.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Elizabeth's Medical Center) is located in the Brighton neighborhood.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] New England Baptist Hospital is in Mission Hill.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The city has Veterans Affairs medical centers in the Jamaica Plain and West Roxbury neighborhoods.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Logan International Airport, in East Boston and operated by the Massachusetts Port Authority (Massport), is Boston's principal airport.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Nearby general aviation airports are Beverly Regional Airport and Lawrence Municipal Airport to the north, Hanscom Field to the west, and Norwood Memorial Airport to the south.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Massport also operates several major facilities within the Port of Boston, including a cruise ship terminal and facilities to handle bulk and container cargo in South Boston, and other facilities in Charlestown and East Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Downtown Boston's streets grew organically, so they do not form a planned grid, unlike those in later-developed Back Bay, East Boston, the South End, and South Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston is the eastern terminus of I-90, which in Massachusetts runs along the Massachusetts Turnpike.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The Central Artery follows I-93 as the primary north–south artery that carries most of the through traffic in Downtown Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Other major highways include US 1, which carries traffic to the North Shore and areas south of Boston, US 3, which connects to the northwestern suburbs, MA 3, which connects to the South Shore and Cape Cod, and MA 2 which connects to the western suburbs.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Surrounding the city is MA 128, a partial beltway which has been largely subsumed by other routes (mostly I-95 and I-93).
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] With nearly a third of Bostonians using public transit for their commute to work, Boston has the sixth-highest rate of public transit usage in the country.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The city of Boston has a higher than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] In 2016, 33.8 percent of Boston households lacked a car, compared with the national average of 8.7 percent.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The city averaged 0.94 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston's public transportation agency, the Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority (MBTA), operates the oldest underground rapid transit system in the Americas and is the fourth-busiest rapid transit system in the country, with 65.5 mi (105 km) of track on four lines.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The MBTA also operates busy bus, commuter rail, and ferry networks.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Amtrak intercity rail to Boston is provided through four stations: South Station, North Station, Back Bay, and Route 128.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] South Station is a major intermodal transportation hub and is the terminus of Amtrak's *Northeast Regional*, *Acela Express*, and *Lake Shore Limited* routes, in addition to multiple MBTA services.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Back Bay is also served by MBTA and those three Amtrak routes, while Route 128, in the southwestern suburbs of Boston, is only served by the *Acela Express* and *Northeast Regional*.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Meanwhile, Amtrak's *Downeaster* to Brunswick, Maine terminates in North Station, and is the only Amtrak route to do so.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Nicknamed "The Walking City", Boston hosts more pedestrian commuters than do other comparably populated cities.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Owing to factors such as necessity, the compactness of the city and large student population, 13 percent of the population commutes by foot, making it the highest percentage of pedestrian commuters in the country out of the major American cities.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] As of 2024, Walk Score ranks Boston as the third most walkable U.S. city, with a Walk Score of 83, a Transit Score of 72, and a Bike Score of 69.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] Boston has one of the highest rates of bicycle commuting.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The bikeshare program Bluebikes, originally called Hubway, launched in late July 2011.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] The system has 480 stations with a total of 4,500 bikes.
[src:alice-bache-gould/boston-p02] PBSC Urban Solutions provides bicycles and technology for this bike-sharing system.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Bryn Mawr College is a private women's liberal arts college founded in 1885.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The name "*bryn mawr*" is Welsh for big hill.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] It is named after the town of Bryn Mawr, in which the campus is located.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The town of Bryn Mawr had previously been named Humphreysville, after the Humphreys family who had bought the land in 1683.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The town was renamed Bryn Mawr in the mid-nineteenth century by the Pennsylvania Railroad Corporation.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Bryn Mawr had been the name of an estate granted to Rowland Ellis by William Penn in the 1680s.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Ellis named it after his former home, a house near Dolgellau, Merioneth, Wales.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The college was largely funded through the bequest of Joseph W.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Taylor, and its first president was James Rhoads.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Bryn Mawr was one of the first institutions of higher education in the United States to offer graduate degrees, including doctorates, to women.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The first class included 36 undergraduate women and eight graduate students.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Bryn Mawr was originally affiliated with the Quakers (Religious Society of Friends), but by 1893 had become non-denominational.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] In 1912, Bryn Mawr became the first college in the United States to offer doctorates in social work, through the Department of Social Economy and Social Research.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] This department became the Graduate School of Social Work and Social Research in 1970.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] In 1931, Bryn Mawr began accepting men as graduate students, while remaining women-focused at the undergraduate level.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] From 1921 to 1938 the Bryn Mawr campus was home to the Bryn Mawr Summer School for Women Workers in Industry, which was founded as part of the labor education movement and the women's labor movement.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The school taught political economy, science, and literature.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The college celebrated its 125th anniversary of "bold vision, for women, for the world" during the 2010–2011 academic year.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] In September 2010, Bryn Mawr hosted an international conference on issues of educational access, equity, and opportunity in secondary schools and universities in the United States and around the world.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Other festivities held for the anniversary year included publication of a commemorative book on 125 years of student life, and, in partnership with the Philadelphia Mural Arts Program, the creation of a mural in West Philadelphia highlighting advances in women's education.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] On February 9, 2015, the college's board of trustees announced approval of a working group recommendation to expand the undergraduate applicant pool allowing transgender women and intersex individuals identifying as women to apply for admission.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] This decision made Bryn Mawr the fourth women's college in the United States to accept trans women.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Bryn Mawr "recognizes that gender is fluid and that traditional notions of gender identity and expression can be limiting", and has the official policy of accepting nonbinary students who were assigned female at birth as well.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] All current, past, and future students are fully recognized as members of the Bryn Mawr community, regardless of current gender identity.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The campus is in the municipality of Lower Merion Township.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Most of the campus is in the Bryn Mawr census-designated place.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The campus was designed in part by noted landscape designers Calvert Vaux and Frederick Law Olmsted, and has subsequently been designated an arboretum (the Bryn Mawr Campus Arboretum).
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The majority of Bryn Mawr students live on campus in residence halls.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Many of the older residence halls were designed by Cope & Stewardson (same architects who designed a large part of the University of Pennsylvania, Washington University in St.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Louis, and Princeton University campuses) and are known for their Collegiate Gothic architecture, modeled after Cambridge University.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Each is named after a county town in Wales: Brecon, Denbigh (1891), Merion (1885), and Radnor (1887), and Pembroke East and West (1892).
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Rhoads North and South was named after the college's first president, James E.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Rhoads; Rockefeller is named after its donor, John D.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Erdman was opened in 1965, designed by architect Louis Kahn.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] In addition, students may choose to live in Batten House (an environmentally friendly co-op).
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Perry House, which was originally established as the Spanish language house in 1962, was redefined as the Black Cultural Center in the 1970s.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] In 2015, Perry House was relaunched by the college in the former French tower of Haffner, which had undergone renovations and reconstruction the previous year.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Along with Perry, now known as the Enid Cook '31 Center, a new residence hall was built where the old Haffner Language and Culture House once stood.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Glenmede (formerly graduate student housing) is an estate located about a half mile from the main campus which at one point was available housing for undergraduate students.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] In 2007, it was sold to a conservation buyer as the annual costs of upkeep were too great for the college.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Olmsted designed a private garden for M.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The garden was later modified and renamed as the Blanca Noel Taft Memorial Garden.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] In its current form, the garden is a small enclosure with two wall fountains, one with a small basin and the other with a sunken reflecting pool.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The decorative wall tiles above the smaller wall fountain and basin were purchased from Syria.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Kahn and Bryn Mawr College president, Katharine Elizabeth McBride, came together to create the Erdman Hall dormitory.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The Marjorie Walter Goodhart Theater houses a vaulted auditorium designed by Arthur Ingersoll Meigs of Mellor, Meigs & Howe, two smaller spaces that are ideal for intimate performances by visiting artists, practice rooms for student musicians, and the Office for the Arts.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The building's towers and gables, friezes, carvings and ornamental ironwork, designed by Samuel Yellin, were done in the gothic revival style.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] In the fall of 2009, the college completed a renovation of Goodhart.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Previously named after Bryn Mawr's first Dean and second president, Old Library was used as the primary campus library until 1970, when Mariam Coffin Canaday Library opened.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The Great Hall (formerly the reading room of the library) was designed by Walter Cope (of Cope and Stewardson) in 1901 and built by Stewardson and Jamieson several years later, although M.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Carey Thomas played a large part in its construction.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Today, it is a space for performances, readings, lectures, and public gatherings.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Old Library encloses a large open courtyard called "The Cloisters".
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Carey Thomas and Emmy Noether are located in the Cloisters.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Georgiana Goddard King is also buried in the cloister.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The building was declared a National Historic Landmark in 1991.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The Great Hall was once the home of an Athena Lemnia statue (damaged in 1997) that is now located in a high alcove in the Rhys Carpenter Art and Archaeology Library.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] A plaster cast of that Athena now stands in her place at the Great Hall.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Students often leave offerings to this statue in the hope that she will intervene on their behalf.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] In 2018, the board of trustees formalized the use of the name "The Old Library".
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Old Library was formerly known as "Thomas Hall" after Bryn Mawr's second president, M.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The building was informally known as "College Hall" for a year before being officially renamed to "Old Library" in 2018.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] This renaming was in response to student protests, which claimed that many of M.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Carey Thomas's views did not represent the values of the college.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Carey Thomas was a virulent eugenicist, antisemite and racist who strongly opposed the admission of students who were not elite white women.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Today, the building houses a plaque explaining the controversy of the former name and affirming the college's current dedication to equity and inclusion, which was unveiled during the 2019 Community Day of Learning.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Named for Bryn Mawr's late professor of Classical Archaeology, the Rhys Carpenter Library was designed by Henry Myerberg of New York and opened in 1997.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The space is connected to the rear of Old Library.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Names of art and archaeology faculty are displayed on the main wall of the atrium, along with a series of plaster casts of the metopes of the Parthenon.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The roof comprises a wide grassy area used for outdoor concerts and picnics.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The building won a 2001 Award of Excellence for Library Architecture from the Library Administration and Management Association and the American Institute of Architects.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Carpenter Library also houses the college's renowned collections in Classical and Near Eastern Archaeology, History of Art, and Classics.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The Bryn Mawr College Deanery was the campus residence of the first Dean and second President of Bryn Mawr College, M.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Carey Thomas, who maintained a home there from 1885 to 1933.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Under the direction of Thomas, the Deanery was gradually enlarged and elaborately decorated with the assistance of the American artist Lockwood de Forest and furnished with art from Thomas' world travels.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] From 1933 until 1968, the Deanery served as the Alumnae Center and Inn for the college.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The building was demolished in the spring of 1968 to make space for the construction of Canaday Library, which stands on the site today.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] At the time of its demolition, many of the Deanery's furnishings were re-located to Wyndham, an 18th-century farmhouse (with several modern additions) which became the college's new Alumnae Center.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Bryn Mawr is a small, four year, residential baccalaureate college.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Although the college offers several graduate programs, the majority of enrollments are from students enrolled in the undergraduate arts and sciences program.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Students at Bryn Mawr are required to complete divisional requirements in the social sciences, natural sciences (including lab skills) and humanities.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] In addition, they must complete one year of a foreign language and fulfill a quantitative skills requirement and an Emily Balch Seminar requirement.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The Emily Balch Seminars are similar to courses in freshman composition at other institutions, though focus on a specific topic.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] In 1972, the college founded a year-long post baccalaureate pre-medical program for career changers.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The program remains one of the oldest, most prestigious, and successful in the country — with an over 98% medical school acceptance rate.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Bryn Mawr students can also take classes and major at Haverford College through the Bi-College Consortium.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Students can also take classes at Swarthmore College and the University of Pennsylvania through the Tri-College and the Quaker Consortium.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] For the Class of 2023 (enrolling fall 2019), Bryn Mawr received 3,332 applications, admitted 1,102 (30%), and enrolled 374 students.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] For the freshmen who enrolled, the middle 50% range of SAT scores was 640–740 for evidence-based reading and writing, and 650–770 for math, while the middle 50% ACT composite score range was 29–33.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Students celebrate four major traditions throughout the year, along with other minor traditions.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Parade Night, which happens on the Friday of the first week of classes, is a tradition where the freshman class runs to Taylor Hall, while the upperclassmen throw confetti.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Following this, the first of the three "Step Sings" takes place, during which the student body sing various traditional and pop songs.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The second is Lantern Night, which takes place in late October or early November, where first year students receive a lantern which symbolizes the passing down of knowledge, during a traditional ceremony with songs in Ancient Greek.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Welcome the First Years Week, formerly known as Hell Week, takes place during the early part of the spring semester between February and March.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] It is a time when students complete silly tasks and attend special events created for them by an upperclassman (called a rose) who the freshman (called a bud) personally selects.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] May Day is held on the Sunday after the last day of classes, not on the traditional date of May 1.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] It includes a breakfast of strawberries and cream, a parade, dancing around the traditional Maypole, a feminist alternative called the Mayhole, and student performances.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Dar Williams's song "As Cool As I Am" has become part of May Day, as the song is played during the Mayhole celebration.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The song is even called an "unofficial anthem" for the school.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The traditions are organized and run by two Traditions Mistexes, elected by the student body.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] In addition to major traditions, there are a number of minor traditions.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] These include offerings to a statue of Athena for luck or thanks, using a set of stairs leading up to Taylor Hall called the Senior Steps or down Senior Row, a row of trees in the center of campus unless a student is a senior.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The Friendship Poles, a set of two vertical poles located under the main arch of the Pembroke Dorms, are not supposed to be split by a group walking through, or else those who "split the poles" will no longer be friends.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Additional traditions and superstitions surround the college campus and its facilities and buildings.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The school's dining halls strive to be environmentally sustainable by working to expand their local and organic offerings, recycling in all dining areas, and recycling used fry oil as bio-diesel fuel.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The dining halls previously offered biodegradable takeout containers, but reverted to Styrofoam in the 2009/10 academic year.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Additionally, all leftover food is donated to a local food bank.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] On the College Sustainability Report Card 2011, published by the Sustainable Endowments Institute, Bryn Mawr received a B+.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The school's highest category score was an A in Investment Priorities, since Bryn Mawr invests in renewable energy funds.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Bryn Mawr College teams are nicknamed *Owls*.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] They play in the Centennial Conference and field intercollegiate teams in badminton, basketball, cross country, field hockey, lacrosse, rowing, soccer, swimming, tennis, indoor and outdoor track and field, and volleyball.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The badminton team won national intercollegiate championships in 1996 and 2008.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] The mascot of the college is the owl, the symbol of Athena, Greek goddess of wisdom.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] A large number of Bryn Mawr alumnae and former attendees are notable in their respective fields.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] 1894); archaeologist Doreen Canaday Spitzer (1936); author, social activist and feminist Grace Lee Boggs (Ph.D.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] 1940); Nobel Peace Prize winner Emily Greene Balch (1889); geneticist Nettie Stevens (Ph.D.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] 1901); physicist and astronomer Frances Lowater (Ph.D.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] 1904); mathematician Ada Isabel Maddison (Ph.D.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Byatt; biologist and science fiction novelist Joan Slonczewski (1977); fantasy novelist Caroline Stevermer; author and memoirist Rachel Simon; actor Maggie Siff (1996); and neuroscientist Candace Pert (1970), who helped discover opioid receptors.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Other notable alumni include Ana Botín, chair of the Santander Group, one of the world's largest banking groups; indie musician Michelle Zauner (2011), who performs as Japanese Breakfast; the social reformer Alice P.
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Gannett (1898), for whom the Goodrich-Gannett Neighborhood Center is named; Maya Ajmera, CEO of Society for Science & the Public; the American balloonist, scientist, teacher and priest Jeannette Piccard (1918); and podcaster and comedian Matt McCusker (2020).
[src:alice-bache-gould/bryn-mawr-college] Notable faculty include Woodrow Wilson, chemists Arthur C.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Founded in December 1630 during the colonial era, Cambridge was one among the first cities established in the Thirteen Colonies, and it went on to play a historic role during the American Revolution.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In May 1775, approximately 16,000 American patriots assembled in Cambridge Common to begin organizing a military retaliation against British troops following the Battles of Lexington and Concord.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] On July 2, 1775, two weeks after the Second Continental Congress in Philadelphia formally established the Continental Army and appointed George Washington commander of it, Washington arrived at Cambridge Common to take command of the Patriot soldiers camped there.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Many of these soldiers played a role in supporting Washington's successful siege of Boston, which trapped garrisoned British troops from moving by land, forcing the British to ultimately abandon Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge Common is thus celebrated as the birthplace of the Continental Army.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Harvard University, an Ivy League university founded in Cambridge in 1636, is the oldest institution of higher learning in the United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT), a private research university, has its 168-acre campus in Cambridge.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Kendall Square, near MIT in the eastern part of Cambridge, has been called "the most innovative square mile on the planet" due to the high concentration of startup companies that have emerged there since 2010.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 2022, Cambridge was home to over 250 biotech companies, with more than 120 located within the Kendall Square ZIP Code.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Native Americans inhabited the Charles River basin for thousands of years prior to European colonization of the Americas, as confirmed by archaeological remains in neighboring Watertown and Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] At the time of European contact, the area was inhabited by Naumkeag of the Pawtucket Confederacy to the north and Massachusett to the south.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The contact period introduced a number of European infectious diseases which would decimate native populations in virgin soil epidemics, significantly depopulating the Charles River basin upon the arrival of large groups of English settlers in the 1630s.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] A deed for the land that includes present-day Cambridge was ultimately obtained from the Naumkeag Squaw Sachem of Mistick in 1639, after a leptospirosis epidemic in 1616–1619 and a smallpox epidemic in 1633 killed large portions of her tribe, including two of her sons.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The first settlement of the Massachusetts Bay Colony was established in Salem, in June of 1626.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] That December, the site of present-day Cambridge was chosen for development because it was safely upriver from Boston Harbor, making it easily defensible from attacks by enemy ships.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The city was founded by Thomas Dudley, his daughter Anne Bradstreet, and his son-in-law Simon Bradstreet.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The first houses were built in the spring of 1631.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The settlement was initially referred to as "the newe towne".
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Official Massachusetts records show the name rendered as **Newe Towne** by 1632, and as **Newtowne** by 1638.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Located at the first convenient Charles River crossing west of Boston, Newtowne was one of several towns, including Boston, Dorchester, Watertown, and Weymouth, founded by the 700 original Puritan colonists of the Massachusetts Bay Colony who arrived on the Winthrop Fleet.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Its first preacher was Thomas Hooker, who led many of its original inhabitants west in 1636 to found Hartford and the Connecticut Colony; before leaving, they sold their plots to more recent immigrants from England.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The original village site is now within Harvard Square.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The marketplace where farmers sold crops from surrounding towns at the edge of a salt marsh (since filled) remains within a small park at the corner of John F.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1636, Newe College, later renamed Harvard College after benefactor John Harvard, was founded as North America's first institution of higher learning.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Its initial purpose was training ministers.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] According to Cotton Mather, Newtowne was chosen for the site of the college by the Great and General Court, then the legislature of the Massachusetts Bay Colony, primarily for its proximity to the popular and highly respected Puritan preacher Thomas Shepard.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In May 1638, the settlement's name was changed to Cambridge in honor of the University of Cambridge in Cambridge, England.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1639, the Great and General Court purchased the land that became present-day Cambridge from the Naumkeag Squaw Sachem of Mistick.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In the late 19th century, various schemes for annexing Cambridge to Boston were pursued and rejected.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Newtowne's ministers, Hooker and Shepard, the college's first president, the college's major benefactor, and the first schoolmaster Nathaniel Eaton were all Cambridge alumni, as was the colony's governor John Winthrop.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1629, Winthrop had led the signing of the founding document of the city of Boston, which was known as the Cambridge Agreement, after the university.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1650, Governor Thomas Dudley signed the charter creating the corporation that still governs Harvard College.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge grew slowly as an agricultural village eight miles (13 km) by road from Boston, the colony's capital.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] By the American Revolution, most residents lived near the Common and Harvard College, with most of the town comprising farms and estates.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] On January 24, 1776, Henry Knox arrived with an artillery train captured from Fort Ticonderoga, which allowed Washington to force the British Army to evacuate Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Most of the Loyalist estates in Cambridge were confiscated after the Revolutionary War.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Between 1790 and 1840, Cambridge grew rapidly with the construction of West Boston Bridge in 1792 connecting Cambridge directly to Boston, making it no longer necessary to travel eight miles (13 km) through the Boston Neck, Roxbury, and Brookline to cross the Charles River.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] A second bridge, the Canal Bridge, opened in 1809 alongside the new Middlesex Canal.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The new bridges and roads made what were formerly estates and marshland into prime industrial and residential districts.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In the mid-19th century, Cambridge was the center of a literary revolution.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It was home to some of the famous Fireside poets, named because their poems would often be read aloud by families in front of their evening fires.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Fireside poets, including Henry Wadsworth Longfellow, James Russell Lowell, and Oliver Wendell Holmes, were highly popular and influential in this era.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In addition, the town was connected to the Boston & Maine Railroad, leading to the development of Porter Square as well as the creation of neighboring Somerville from the formerly rural parts of Charlestown.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge was incorporated as a city in 1846.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The city's commercial center began to shift from Harvard Square to Central Square, which became the city's downtown around that time.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] For much of the 19th and early 20th centuries, the city's largest employer was the New England Glass Company, founded in 1818.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, it was the world's largest and most modern glassworks.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1888, Edward Drummond Libbey moved all production to Toledo, Ohio, where it continues today under the name Owens-Illinois.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The company's flint glassware with heavy lead content is prized by antique glass collectors, and the Toledo Museum of Art has a large collection.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Museum of Fine Arts in Boston and the Sandwich Glass Museum on Cape Cod also house several pieces.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1895, Edwin Ginn, founder of Ginn and Company, built the Athenaeum Press Building for his publishing textbook empire.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] By 1920, Cambridge was one of New England's main industrial cities, with nearly 120,000 residents.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Among the largest businesses in Cambridge during the period of industrialization was Carter's Ink Company, whose neon sign long adorned the Charles River and which was for many years the world's largest ink manufacturer.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Welch (1927–1963, originator of Junior Mints, Sugar Daddies, Sugar Mamas, and Sugar Babies, now part of Tootsie Roll Industries).
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Main Street was nicknamed "Confectioner's Row".
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Only the Cambridge Brands subsidiary of Tootsie Roll Industries remains in town, still manufacturing Junior Mints in the old Welch factory on Main Street.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Blake and Knowles Steam Pump Company (1886), the Kendall Boiler and Tank Company (1880, now in Chelmsford, Massachusetts), and the New England Glass Company (1818–1878) were among the industrial manufacturers in what are now Kendall Square and East Cambridge.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1935, the Cambridge Housing Authority and the Public Works Administration demolished an integrated low-income tenement neighborhood with African Americans and European immigrants.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In its place, it built the whites-only "Newtowne Court" public housing development and the adjoining, blacks-only "Washington Elms" project in 1940; the city required segregation in its other public housing projects as well.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] As industry in New England began to decline during the Great Depression and after World War II, Cambridge lost much of its industrial base.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It also began to become an intellectual, rather than an industrial, center.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Harvard University, which had always been important as both a landowner and an institution, began to play a more dominant role in the city's life and culture.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] When Radcliffe College was established in 1879, the town became a mecca for some of the nation's most academically talented female students.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] MIT's move from Boston to Cambridge in 1916 reinforced Cambridge's status as an intellectual center of the United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] After the 1950s, the city's population began to decline slowly as families tended to be replaced by single people and young couples.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In Cambridge Highlands, the technology company Bolt, Beranek, & Newman produced the first network router in 1969 and hosted the invention of computer-to-computer email in 1971.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The 1980s brought a wave of high technology startups.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Those selling advanced minicomputers were overtaken by the microcomputer.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge-based VisiCorp made the first spreadsheet software for personal computers, VisiCalc, and helped propel the Apple II to consumer success.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It was overtaken and purchased by Cambridge-based Lotus Development, maker of Lotus 1-2-3 (which was, in turn, replaced in by Microsoft Excel).
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The city continues to be home to many startups.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Kendall Square was a software hub through the dot-com boom and today hosts offices of such technology companies as Google, Microsoft, and Amazon.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Square also now houses the headquarters of Akamai.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 1976, Harvard's plans to start experiments with recombinant DNA led to a three-month moratorium and a citizen review panel.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In the end, Cambridge decided to allow such experiments but passed safety regulations in 1977.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] This led to regulatory certainty and acceptance when Biogen opened a lab in 1982, in contrast to the hostility that caused the Genetic Institute, a Harvard spinoff, to abandon Somerville and Boston for Cambridge.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The biotech and pharmaceutical industries have since thrived in Cambridge, which now includes headquarters for Biogen and Genzyme; laboratories for Novartis, Teva, Takeda, Alnylam, Ironwood, Moderna Therapeutics, Editas Medicine; support companies such as Cytel; and many smaller companies.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] During the era of rent control in Massachusetts, at least 20 percent of all rent controlled apartments in Cambridge housed high-income earners, with the majority going to people with professional, technical, and managerial jobs.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In an independent study conducted of 2/3 of the rent controlled apartments in Cambridge in 1988, 246 were households headed by doctors, 298 by lawyers, 265 by architects, 259 by professors, and 220 by engineers.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] There were 2,650 with students, including 1,503 with graduate students.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The end of rent control in 1994 had numerous effects on the city.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Within four years of repealing the law, Cambridge, where "the city's form of rent control was unusually strict," saw new housing and construction increase by 50%, and the tax revenue from construction permits tripled.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Property values in Cambridge increased by about $7.8 billion in the decade following the repeal.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Roughly a quarter of this increase, $1.8 billion ($3 billion in 2024 dollars), was due to the repeal of rent control.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Close to 40% of all Cambridge properties were under rent control when it was repealed.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Their property values appreciated faster than non-rent controlled properties, as did the properties around them.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] By the end of the 20th century, Cambridge had one of the most costly housing markets in the Northeastern United States.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge's mix of amenities and proximity to Boston kept housing prices relatively stable despite the bursting of the United States housing bubble in 2008 and 2009.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge has been a sanctuary city since 1985 and reaffirmed its status as such in 2006.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Census Bureau, Cambridge has a total area of 7.1 square miles (18 km2), 6.4 square miles (17 km2) of which is land and 0.7 square miles (1.8 km2) (9.82%) of which is water.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The border between Cambridge and the neighboring city of Somerville passes through densely populated neighborhoods, which are connected by the MBTA Red Line.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Some of the main squares, Inman, Porter, and to a lesser extent, Harvard and Lechmere, are very close to the city line, as are Somerville's Union and Davis Squares.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Through the City of Cambridge's exclusive municipal water system, the city further controls two exclave areas, one being Payson Park Reservoir and Gatehouse, a 2009 listed American Water Landmark located roughly one mile west of Fresh Pond and surrounded by the town of Belmont.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The second area is the larger Hobbs Brook and Stony Brook watersheds, which share borders with neighboring towns and cities including Lexington, Lincoln, Waltham and Weston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge has been called the "City of Squares", as most of its commercial districts are major street intersections known as squares.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Each square acts as a neighborhood center.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Kendall Square, formed by the junction of Broadway, Main Street, and Third Street, has been called "the most innovative square mile on the planet", owing to its high concentration of entrepreneurial start-ups and quality of innovation which have emerged in the vicinity of the square since 2010.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Technology Square is an office and laboratory building cluster in this neighborhood.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Just over the Longfellow Bridge from Boston, at the eastern end of the MIT campus, it is served by the Kendall/MIT station on the MBTA Red Line subway.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Most of Cambridge's large office towers are located in the Square.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Kendall Square houses some of the biggest technological companies of the world, including Google, Microsoft, Amazon, Meta, and Apple.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] A biotech industry has developed in this area.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Cambridge Innovation Center, a large co-working space, is in Kendall Square at 1 Broadway.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Cambridge Center office complex is in Kendall Square, and not at the actual center of Cambridge.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The "One Kendall Square" complex is nearby, but not actually in Kendall Square.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Central Square is formed by the junction of Massachusetts Avenue, Prospect Street, and Western Avenue.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Containing a variety of ethnic restaurants, it was economically depressed as recently as the late 1990s; it underwent gentrification in recent years (in conjunction with the development of the nearby University Park at MIT), and continues to grow more costly.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It is served by the Central Square stop on the MBTA Red Line subway.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Lafayette Square, formed by the junction of Massachusetts Avenue, Columbia Street, Sidney Street, and Main Street, is considered part of the Central Square area.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridgeport is south of Central Square, and bordered by MIT, the Charles River, Massachusetts Avenue, and River Street.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Harvard Square is formed by the junction of Massachusetts Avenue, Brattle Street, Dunster Street, and JFK Street.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] This is the primary site of Harvard University and a major Cambridge shopping area.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It is served by the Harvard Square Red Line station.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Harvard Square was originally the Red Line's northwestern terminus and a major transfer point to streetcars that also operated in a short tunnel—which is still a major bus terminal, although the area under the Square was reconfigured dramatically in the 1980s when the Red Line was extended.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] A short distance away from the square lies the Cambridge Common, while the neighborhood north of Harvard and east of Massachusetts Avenue is known as Baldwin, in honor of the first Black principal of Cambridge public schools, Maria L.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It was renamed "Baldwin" in 2021, and so some know the area better by its former name, Agassiz, after the famed scientist Louis Agassiz.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Porter Square is about a mile north on Massachusetts Avenue from Harvard Square, at the junction of Massachusetts and Somerville Avenues.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It includes part of the city of Somerville and is served by the Porter Square Station, a complex housing a Red Line stop and a Fitchburg Line commuter rail stop.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Lesley University's University Hall and Porter campus are in Porter Square.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Inman Square is at the junction of Cambridge and Hampshire streets in mid-Cambridge.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It is home to restaurants, bars, music venues, and boutiques.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Victorian streetlights, benches, and bus stops were added to the streets in the 2000s, and a new city park was installed.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Lechmere Square is at the junction of Cambridge and First streets, adjacent to the CambridgeSide Galleria shopping mall.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It is served by Lechmere station on the MBTA Green Line.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In the Köppen-Geiger classification, Cambridge has a hot-summer humid continental climate (Dfa) with four well-defined seasons.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Summers are warm to hot, fall and spring are cool and rainy, and winter is cold and gray with occasional snowstorms.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Abundant rain falls on the city (and in the winter often as snow); it has no dry season.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The average January temperature is 26.6 °F (−3 °C), making Cambridge part of Group D, independent of the isotherm.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] As of the census of 2010, there were 105,162 people, 44,032 households, and 17,420 families residing in the city.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The population density was 16,354.9 inhabitants per square mile (6,314.7/km2).
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] There were 47,291 housing units at an average density of 7,354.7 per square mile (2,839.7/km2).
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The racial makeup of the city was 66.60% White, 11.70% Black or African American, 0.20% Native American, 15.10% Asian (3.7% Chinese, 1.4% Asian Indian, 1.2% Korean, 1.0% Japanese), 0.01% Pacific Islander, 2.10% from other races, and 4.30% from two or more races.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] 7.60% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race (1.6% Puerto Rican, 1.4% Mexican, 0.6% Dominican, 0.5% Colombian & Salvadoran, 0.4% Spaniard).
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Non-Hispanic Whites were 62.1% of the population in 2010, down from 89.7% in 1970.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] An individual resident of Cambridge is known as a Cantabrigian.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 2010, there were 44,032 households, out of which 16.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 28.9% were married couples living together, 8.4% had a female householder with no husband present, and 60.4% were non-families.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] 40.7% of all households were made up of individuals, and 9.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The average household size was 2.00 and the average family size was 2.76.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In the city, the population was spread out, with 13.3% of the population under the age of 18, 21.2% from 18 to 24, 38.6% from 25 to 44, 17.8% from 45 to 64, and 9.2% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] For every 100 females, there were 96.1 males.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.7 males.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The median income for a household in the city was $47,979, and the median income for a family was $59,423 (these figures had risen to $58,457 and $79,533 respectively as of a 2007 estimate).
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Males had a median income of $43,825 versus $38,489 for females.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The per capita income for the city was $31,156.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] About 8.7% of families and 12.9% of the population were below the poverty line, including 15.1% of those under age 18 and 12.9% of those age 65 or over.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Locals living in and near the city jokingly refer to it as "The People's Republic of Cambridge".
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] For 2016, the residential property tax rate in Cambridge was $6.99 per $1,000.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge enjoys the highest possible bond credit rating, AAA, with all three Wall Street rating agencies.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 2000, 11.0% of city residents were of Irish ancestry; 7.2% were of English, 6.9% Italian, 5.5% West Indian and 5.3% German ancestry.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] 69.4% spoke only English at home, while 6.9% spoke Spanish, 3.2% Chinese or Mandarin, 3.0% Portuguese, 2.9% French Creole, 2.3% French, 1.5% Korean, and 1.0% Italian.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Data is from the 2009–2013 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Manufacturing was an important part of Cambridge's economy in the late 19th and early 20th century.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Since the late 20th century, Kendall Square and adjacent areas have shifted from primarily industrial uses toward biotechnology, laboratory, office, and mixed-use development.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] As a cradle of technological innovation, Cambridge was home to technology firms Analog Devices, Akamai, Bolt, Beranek, and Newman (BBN Technologies) (now part of Raytheon), General Radio (later GenRad), Lotus Development Corporation (now part of IBM), Polaroid, Symbolics, and Thinking Machines.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Little, and Lotus were Cambridge's top employers, with over 1,000 employees, but they faded out a few years later.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Health care and biotechnology firms such as Genzyme, Biogen Idec, bluebird bio, Millennium Pharmaceuticals, Sanofi, Pfizer and Novartis have significant presences in the city.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Though headquartered in Switzerland, Novartis continues to expand its operations in Cambridge.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Other major biotech and pharmaceutical firms expanding their presence in Cambridge include GlaxoSmithKline, AstraZeneca, Shire, and Pfizer.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Most of Cambridge's biotech firms are in Kendall Square and East Cambridge, which decades ago were the city's center of manufacturing.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Some others are in University Park at MIT, a new development in another former manufacturing area.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] None of the high technology firms that once dominated the economy was among the 25 largest employers in 2005, but by 2008 Akamai and ITA Software were.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Google, IBM Research, Microsoft Research, and Philips Research maintain offices in Cambridge.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In late January 2012—less than a year after acquiring Billerica-based analytic database management company, Vertica—Hewlett-Packard announced it would also be opening its first offices in Cambridge.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Also around that time, e-commerce giants Staples and Amazon.com said they would be opening research and innovation centers in Kendall Square.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] And LabCentral provides a shared laboratory facility for approximately 25 emerging biotech companies.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The proximity of Cambridge's universities has also made the city a center for nonprofit groups and think tanks, including the National Bureau of Economic Research, the Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory, the Lincoln Institute of Land Policy, Cultural Survival, and Science Club for Girls.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In September 2011, Cambridge launched its Entrepreneur Walk of Fame initiative, recognizing people who have made contributions to innovation in global business.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] In 2021, Cambridge was one of approximately 27 US cities to receive a AAA rating from each of the three major US credit rating agencies, Moody's Investors Service, Standard & Poor's and Fitch Ratings.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] 2021 marked the 22nd consecutive year that Cambridge had retained this distinction.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge's massive tax base has allowed it to keep residential taxes fairly low, and its budget is the second largest in the state despite being the fourth largest in population.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Cambridge has a large and varied collection of permanent public art, on both city property, managed by the Cambridge Arts Council, Community Art Center, and the Harvard and MIT campuses.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Temporary public artworks are displayed as part of the annual Cambridge River Festival on the banks of the Charles River during winter celebrations in Harvard and Central Squares and at Harvard University campus sites.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Experimental forms of public artistic and cultural expression include the Central Square World's Fair, the annual Somerville-based Honk!
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Festival, and If This House Could Talk, a neighborhood art and history event.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Street musicians and other performers entertain tourists and locals in Harvard Square during the warmer months.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The performances are coordinated through a public process that has been developed collaboratively by the performers, city administrators, private organizations and business groups.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The Cambridge public library contains four Works Progress Administration murals completed in 1935 by Elizabeth Tracy Montminy: *Religion*, *Fine Arts*, *History of Books and Paper*, and *The Development of the Printing Press*.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Despite intensive urbanization during the late 19th century and the 20th century, Cambridge has several historic buildings, including some from the 17th century.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The city also has abundant contemporary architecture, largely built by Harvard and MIT.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] The city has an active music scene, from classical performances to the latest popular bands.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Beyond its colleges and universities, Cambridge has many music venues, including The Middle East, Club Passim, The Plough and Stars, The Lizard Lounge and the Nameless Coffeehouse.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Consisting largely of densely built residential space, Cambridge lacks significant tracts of public parkland.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Easily accessible open space on the university campuses, including Harvard Yard, Radcliffe Yard, and MIT's Great Lawn, as well as the considerable open space of Mount Auburn Cemetery and Fresh Pond Reservation, partly compensates for this.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] At Cambridge's western edge, the cemetery is known as a garden cemetery because of its landscaping (the oldest planned landscape in the country) and arboretum.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Although known as a Cambridge landmark, much of the cemetery lies within Watertown.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] It is also an Important Bird Area (IBA) in the Greater Boston area.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Fresh Pond Reservation is the largest open green space in Cambridge with 162 acres (656,000 m2) of land around a 155-acre (627,000 m2) kettle hole lake.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] This land includes a 2.25-mile walking trail around the reservoir and a public nine-hole golf course.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p01] Public parkland includes the esplanade along the Charles River, which mirrors its Boston counterpart, Cambridge Common, Danehy Park, and Alewife Brook Reservation.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge is split between Massachusetts's 5th and 7th U.S. congressional districts.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The 5th district seat is held by Democrat Katherine Clark, who replaced now-Senator Ed Markey in a 2013 special election; the 7th is represented by Democrat Ayanna Pressley, elected in 2018.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The state's senior United States senator is Democrat Elizabeth Warren, elected in 2012, who lives in Cambridge.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The governor of Massachusetts is Democrat Maura Healey, elected in 2022.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The city is represented in the Massachusetts Senate as a part of the 2nd Middlesex, Middlesex and Suffolk, and 1st Suffolk and Middlesex districts.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] From 1860 to 1880, Republicans Abraham Lincoln, Ulysses S.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Hayes, and James Garfield each won Cambridge, Grant doing so by margins of over 20 points in both of his campaigns.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Following that, from 1884 to 1892, Grover Cleveland won Cambridge in all three of his presidential campaigns, by less than ten points each time.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Then from 1896 to 1924, Cambridge became something of a swing city with a slight Republican lean.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Republican candidates carried the city in five of the eight presidential elections during that time, with five of the elections resulting in either a plurality or a margin of victory of fewer than ten points.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] In the last 23 presidential elections, dating back to the nomination of Al Smith in the 1928 presidential election, Democratic presidential candidates have won Cambridge with every Democratic nominee since Massachusetts native John F.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Kennedy in 1960 receiving at least 70% of the vote, except for Jimmy Carter in 1976 and 1980.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Since 1928, the only Republican nominee to come within ten points of carrying Cambridge is Dwight Eisenhower in his 1956 reelection bid.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge has consistently voted for left-wing causes, such as ranked-choice voting, marijuana legalization, and physician-assisted suicide.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge has a city government led by a mayor and a nine-member city council.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] There is also a six-member school committee that functions alongside the superintendent of public schools.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The councilors and school committee members are elected every two years using proportional representation.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The mayor is elected by the city councilors from among themselves and serves as the chair of city council meetings.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The mayor also sits on the school committee.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The mayor is not the city's chief executive.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Rather, the city manager, who is appointed by the city council, serves in that capacity.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Under the city's Plan E form of government, the city council does not have the power to appoint or remove city officials who are under the direction of the city manager.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The city council and its members are also forbidden from giving orders to any subordinate of the city manager.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Yi-An Huang is the City Manager as of September 6, 2022, succeeding Owen O'Riordan (now the Deputy City Manager) who briefly served as the Acting City Manager after Louis DePasquale resigned on July 5, 2022, after six years in office.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge was a county seat of Middlesex County, along with Lowell, until the abolition of executive county government.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Though the county government was abolished in 1997, the county still exists as a geographical and political region.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The employees of Middlesex County courts, jails, registries, and other county agencies are now employed directly by the Commonwealth.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The county's registry of Deeds remain in Cambridge, but the Probate and Family Court, Superior Court, District Attorney's and Sheriff's offices have had their operations transferred roughly nine miles north to Woburn.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The local Third District Court has shifted operations to Medford.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The Middlesex County Jail & House of Correction was also relocated 25 miles north from Cambridge to Billerica in 2014.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] At least 258 of the world's total 962 Nobel Prize winners have at some point in their careers been affiliated with universities in Cambridge.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Radcliffe College, a women's liberal arts college, was based in Cambridge from its 1879 founding until its assimilation into Harvard in 1999.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge College is named for Cambridge and was based in Cambridge until 2017, when it consolidated to a new headquarters in neighboring Boston.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The American Academy of Arts and Sciences, one of the nation's oldest learned societies founded in 1780, is based in Cambridge.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The city's schools constitute the Cambridge Public School District.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge has three district public high school programs, including Cambridge Rindge and Latin School.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] As part of the Metro Boston area, the city's primary network-affiliated television stations are WBTS-CD (NBC), WBZ-TV (CBS), WCVB-TV (ABC), and WFXT (Fox).
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Boston's CW affiliate, WLVI, is licensed to Cambridge.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] There are several additional local stations that are accessible over the air.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The city also is served by WGBH-TV and WGBX-TV, which are PBS member stations, with WGBH being the flagship station of the statewide WGBH Educational Foundation network.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Several TV services provide different portions of Cambridge with cable, DSL, fiber and satellite TV broadcasts and Internet including AT&T U-verse/DIRECTV, Comcast/Xfinity, and DISH Network.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Due to close proximity with Somerville, local media frequently covers events and local topics of interest in both municipalities.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge is served by the online newspaper *Cambridge Day*, which was created in 2009 by Marc Levy.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] *Cambridge Day* became a nonprofit in 2024.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Levy left over differences of opinion and formed the *Cambridge Somerville Independent* in 2026.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The competing *Cambridge Chronicle* ceased publication in 2022 and today only cross-posts regional stories from other Gannett properties like Wicked Local.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Student-led newspapers of Harvard University, known respectively as The Harvard Crimson and The Harvard Independent, alongside The Tech of MIT, or the Register Forum of Cambridge Rindge & Latin High School also lightly feature local topics of interest as well.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] *The Boston Globe* publishes the "Camberville" section which covers Cambridge and Somerville.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Other hyperlocal online journalism such as Patch Media feature news about Cambridge as well.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The City of Cambridge's Public Library maintains a digital archive of many past local newspaper issues as part of its circulation.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge Community Television (CCTV) has served the city since its inception in 1988.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] CCTV operates Cambridge's public access television facility and three television channels, 8, 9, and 96, on the XFinity cable system (Comcast).
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The city has invited tenders from other cable providers, but Comcast remains its only fixed television and broadband utility, though services from American satellite TV providers are available.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Cambridge obtains water from Hobbs Brook (in Lincoln and Waltham) and Stony Brook (Waltham and Weston), as well as an emergency connection to the Massachusetts Water Resources Authority.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The city owns over 1,200 acres (486 ha) of land in other towns that includes these reservoirs and portions of their watershed.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] Water from these reservoirs flows by gravity through an aqueduct to Fresh Pond in Cambridge.
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] It is then treated in an adjacent plant and pumped uphill to an elevation of 176 feet (54 m) above sea level at the Payson Park Reservoir (Belmont).
[src:alice-bache-gould/cambridge-massachusetts-p02] The water is then redistributed downhill via gravity to individual users in the city.
